[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

01:50:17.300 --> 01:50:18.540
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

01:50:18.540 --> 01:50:23.260
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Naushad Forbes about his wonderful book, The Struggle and The Promise

01:50:23.260 --> 01:50:26.900
[Amit Varma]: and the emphasis there, of course, being on the promise.

01:50:26.900 --> 01:50:30.760
[Amit Varma]: But we have to talk about the struggle as well.

01:50:30.760 --> 01:50:35.660
[Amit Varma]: So we've spoken about sort of this longest sweep of history of the scribe, where once

01:50:35.660 --> 01:50:36.660
[Amit Varma]: there was much more inequality.

01:50:36.660 --> 01:50:38.020
[Amit Varma]: We were all equally poor.

01:50:38.020 --> 01:50:39.860
[Amit Varma]: That's the way the world was.

01:50:39.860 --> 01:50:41.580
[Amit Varma]: Things changed over the centuries.

01:50:41.580 --> 01:50:43.660
[Amit Varma]: And eventually we got here.

01:50:43.660 --> 01:50:49.180
[Amit Varma]: Now tell me a little bit about India, like you, you quoted from this economist article

01:50:49.180 --> 01:50:54.380
[Amit Varma]: of 1991, where eloquently you said, quote, the economist did a survey of the Indian economy

01:50:54.380 --> 01:50:59.660
[Amit Varma]: in June 1991, in which it said, and now you're quoting the economist, nowhere in the world

01:50:59.660 --> 01:51:04.700
[Amit Varma]: is a gap between what might have been achieved and what has been achieved as great as it

01:51:04.700 --> 01:51:05.940
[Amit Varma]: is in India, stop good.

01:51:05.940 --> 01:51:09.380
[Amit Varma]: And it reminded me of another famous quote, but I can't for the life of me remember who

01:51:09.380 --> 01:51:13.220
[Amit Varma]: said it, which is that the saddest words in the English language are the words that might

01:51:13.220 --> 01:51:14.220
[Amit Varma]: have been.

01:51:14.220 --> 01:51:15.220
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:51:15.220 --> 01:51:21.500
[Amit Varma]: You know, so lay out briefly where we kind of went wrong, because at another point, you

01:51:21.500 --> 01:51:26.900
[Amit Varma]: compare us with Southeast Asia and China, like you again, I'll quote this better.

01:51:26.900 --> 01:51:31.260
[Amit Varma]: In 1960, South Korea and India had much the same per capita GDP.

01:51:31.260 --> 01:51:35.980
[Amit Varma]: In 1980, China and India had much the same per capita GDP.

01:51:35.980 --> 01:51:40.020
[Amit Varma]: South Korea at $32,000 is now 15 times richer than we are.

01:51:40.020 --> 01:51:43.620
[Amit Varma]: And China at $10,300 is five times richer.

01:51:43.620 --> 01:51:45.580
[Amit Varma]: It's all a matter of growth rates.

01:51:45.580 --> 01:51:48.460
[Amit Varma]: And then you talk about the different growth rates and all that.

01:51:48.460 --> 01:51:55.720
[Amit Varma]: So you know, where did we go wrong in broad strokes, if you can sort of paint that picture.

01:51:55.720 --> 01:51:59.540
[Guest]: So where we went wrong, I mean, and this is not, this is not me.

01:51:59.540 --> 01:52:03.440
[Guest]: This is, you know, many, many economists, Jagdish Bhagwati and many others who've talked

01:52:03.440 --> 01:52:13.340
[Guest]: about this, is really in the role of the state and the trade policy that we followed.

01:52:13.340 --> 01:52:16.820
[Guest]: And the role of the state was increasingly intrusive.

01:52:16.820 --> 01:52:21.300
[Guest]: It brought in controls and regulations and so on.

01:52:21.300 --> 01:52:25.080
[Guest]: This particularly grew after Nehru.

01:52:25.080 --> 01:52:28.680
[Guest]: With Nehru, there were some calls that were perhaps wrong.

01:52:28.680 --> 01:52:34.780
[Guest]: In particular on, I think, the whole role of public sector primacy in the economy, second,

01:52:34.780 --> 01:52:40.620
[Guest]: you know, locating public R&D in autonomous R&D institutions instead of in the higher

01:52:40.620 --> 01:52:47.300
[Guest]: education system, and probably emphasizing higher education over school education.

01:52:47.300 --> 01:52:52.540
[Guest]: I would say those three areas were mistakes on Nehru's part.

01:52:52.540 --> 01:52:58.940
[Guest]: But I'm convinced that if Nehru had lived by the late 60s, early 70s, we would have

01:52:58.940 --> 01:53:00.260
[Guest]: changed direction.

01:53:00.260 --> 01:53:08.140
[Guest]: I think where we really went wrong was under Indira Gandhi, where the controls grew in

01:53:08.140 --> 01:53:09.700
[Guest]: the economy.

01:53:09.700 --> 01:53:17.020
[Guest]: It was supplemented by a distrust of institutions that Nehru had really built up in the country,

01:53:17.020 --> 01:53:21.480
[Guest]: independent institutions that he gave a lot of credibility to.

01:53:21.480 --> 01:53:28.180
[Guest]: And as a result, any institution that came in the way of Mrs. Gandhi's way of wanting

01:53:28.180 --> 01:53:34.980
[Guest]: to do things, she squashed and tried to control or change the head off or whatever.

01:53:34.980 --> 01:53:43.060
[Guest]: And a real shift inward in terms of trade policy, you know, and a focus on import substitution,

01:53:43.060 --> 01:53:48.080
[Guest]: you know, very high tariffs, tariffs that got higher with each passing year, a ban on

01:53:48.080 --> 01:53:55.700
[Guest]: imports of all manner of different items, and we became a very inward-looking country.

01:53:55.700 --> 01:54:01.360
[Guest]: Things started to open up under, actually, first under the Janata government, and then

01:54:01.360 --> 01:54:08.020
[Guest]: under Indira Gandhi when she came back in 1980, her last term in government, she started

01:54:08.020 --> 01:54:13.140
[Guest]: to open the economy up a little bit, particularly in terms of technology imports that started

01:54:13.140 --> 01:54:15.380
[Guest]: to open up in the 80s.

01:54:15.380 --> 01:54:21.620
[Guest]: And then the opening up continued under Rajiv Gandhi, again, you know, on technology, on

01:54:21.620 --> 01:54:27.380
[Guest]: foreign investment, on moving away from the public sector, playing a prime role in the

01:54:27.380 --> 01:54:28.380
[Guest]: economy, et cetera.

01:54:28.380 --> 01:54:31.420
[Guest]: That was all that all started under Rajiv Gandhi.

01:54:31.420 --> 01:54:38.140
[Guest]: But the really decisive shift happens in 1991, where you then say, OK, openness on the trade

01:54:38.140 --> 01:54:43.700
[Guest]: policy front, so tariffs come down dramatically, the rupee is devalued to go with the lower

01:54:43.700 --> 01:54:50.060
[Guest]: tariffs, the scrapping of industrial licensing, you add otherwise, we were the only country

01:54:50.060 --> 01:54:55.940
[Guest]: in the world that had maximum capacity restrictions, you know, that if you had a licensed plant,

01:54:55.940 --> 01:55:00.300
[Guest]: you couldn't produce more, you could only produce up to that limit.

01:55:00.300 --> 01:55:05.340
[Guest]: So you know, all of that went, so industrial licensing was scrapped.

01:55:05.340 --> 01:55:11.160
[Guest]: We had a big change, for example, in capital issues, where earlier, you know, any capital

01:55:11.160 --> 01:55:15.820
[Guest]: issue by a company, when they listed, the price of the issue would be determined by

01:55:15.820 --> 01:55:19.380
[Guest]: the controller of capital issues, not by the firm.

01:55:19.380 --> 01:55:22.060
[Guest]: So that was, again, we moved away from that.

01:55:22.060 --> 01:55:25.820
[Guest]: Firms were able to set their own price, decide what to list at.

01:55:25.820 --> 01:55:32.220
[Guest]: And you see a huge boom that takes place in the 90s, with many new enterprises getting

01:55:32.220 --> 01:55:37.740
[Guest]: started, many small firms starting to really take off and grow big, and many of these older

01:55:37.740 --> 01:55:41.640
[Guest]: enterprises that couldn't cope going by the wayside and disappearing.

01:55:41.640 --> 01:55:45.940
[Guest]: So you see that story really starting to emerge from the 90s onwards.

01:55:45.940 --> 01:55:49.620
[Guest]: And it helped that there were sectors that started to emerge then.

01:55:49.620 --> 01:55:53.820
[Guest]: The IT services sector really comes into its own.

01:55:53.820 --> 01:55:58.420
[Guest]: It started earlier, but it really comes into its own in the 90s, where it becomes a big

01:55:58.420 --> 01:55:59.820
[Guest]: engine of growth.

01:55:59.820 --> 01:56:04.660
[Guest]: The pharmaceutical sector, same, comes into its own in the 90s.

01:56:04.660 --> 01:56:09.260
[Guest]: And by the late 90s, the automobile and auto components sector really starts to take off

01:56:09.260 --> 01:56:10.740
[Guest]: and come into its own.

01:56:10.740 --> 01:56:17.940
[Guest]: And those three, I think, industry segments really start to power the India economic story

01:56:17.940 --> 01:56:18.940
[Guest]: going forward.

01:56:18.940 --> 01:56:22.700
[Guest]: And then in the 2000s, we see many new sectors start up.

01:56:22.700 --> 01:56:28.580
[Guest]: A lot of the services sectors that we've seen, whether it's health care, whether it's education,

01:56:28.580 --> 01:56:38.140
[Guest]: and a lot of the services that retail, shopping malls, construction, a huge construction boom,

01:56:38.140 --> 01:56:44.420
[Guest]: and so on, which sort of joins the India growth story.

01:56:44.420 --> 01:56:45.900
[Amit Varma]: So here's again a broader question.

01:56:45.900 --> 01:56:50.860
[Amit Varma]: Like, first of all, before the broader question, obviously, I think people often understate

01:56:50.860 --> 01:56:53.060
[Amit Varma]: how bad Indira truly was.

01:56:53.060 --> 01:56:57.180
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, people remember her for the emergency, but I just think that her economic

01:56:57.180 --> 01:56:59.980
[Amit Varma]: policies were crimes on humanity.

01:56:59.980 --> 01:57:00.980
[Guest]: Economic policies were terrible.

01:57:00.980 --> 01:57:01.980
[Amit Varma]: Were terrible.

01:57:01.980 --> 01:57:04.900
[Amit Varma]: They kept millions in poverty for decades longer than necessary.

01:57:04.900 --> 01:57:06.660
[Guest]: And was all sloganeering.

01:57:06.660 --> 01:57:14.700
[Guest]: You know, this Gareebi Hatao was a populist slogan to end all populist slogans.

01:57:14.700 --> 01:57:21.700
[Guest]: And you know, it was a classic illustration of trying to fool enough people, you know,

01:57:21.700 --> 01:57:27.740
[Guest]: to get reelected without actually wanting to do anything that improved matters.

01:57:27.740 --> 01:57:29.820
[Amit Varma]: So here's the broader question.

01:57:29.820 --> 01:57:35.580
[Amit Varma]: Like when we look back, I think that fundamentally, it is not simply a question of choosing this

01:57:35.580 --> 01:57:36.620
[Amit Varma]: policy over that.

01:57:36.620 --> 01:57:37.620
[Amit Varma]: It is a mindset issue.

01:57:37.620 --> 01:57:41.540
[Amit Varma]: Like Nehru famously once said to JRD Tata that, you know, quote, do not talk to me of

01:57:41.540 --> 01:57:42.540
[Amit Varma]: profit.

01:57:42.540 --> 01:57:43.540
[Amit Varma]: It is a dirty word.

01:57:43.540 --> 01:57:44.540
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:57:44.540 --> 01:57:48.060
[Amit Varma]: You also mentioned in your book about how when it comes to what we would today call

01:57:48.060 --> 01:57:52.340
[Amit Varma]: Atman Nirbharta, he once said, I'd rather have a secondhand product made in India than

01:57:52.340 --> 01:57:54.500
[Amit Varma]: a first-rate product made elsewhere.

01:57:54.500 --> 01:58:01.860
[Amit Varma]: And that whole mindset that, you know, looking at the economy as a zero-sum game, that mindset

01:58:01.860 --> 01:58:07.380
[Amit Varma]: of that distrust of private enterprise, that desire for the state to control everything,

01:58:07.380 --> 01:58:08.660
[Amit Varma]: a lot came from that mindset.

01:58:08.660 --> 01:58:10.980
[Amit Varma]: Now, we might well say that, okay, it's fine.

01:58:10.980 --> 01:58:12.260
[Amit Varma]: We suffered through that.

01:58:12.260 --> 01:58:15.300
[Amit Varma]: But the arc of history goes towards freedom in this case.

01:58:15.300 --> 01:58:17.740
[Amit Varma]: And 91 happens and so on and so forth.

01:58:17.740 --> 01:58:25.180
[Amit Varma]: But what has happened there is that, you know, you talk about 91 to 2017 as, you know, years

01:58:25.180 --> 01:58:29.860
[Amit Varma]: when we kind of did well, various other economists I speak to like Pooja Mehra, Ajay Shah, Shruti

01:58:29.860 --> 01:58:34.620
[Amit Varma]: Rajgopalan, they would end at 2011 when things kind of start going down.

01:58:34.620 --> 01:58:35.620
[Unknown]: But that's a different matter.

01:58:35.620 --> 01:58:36.620
[Unknown]: That's a technical matter.

01:58:36.620 --> 01:58:40.420
[Amit Varma]: You know, it depends on which indicators you're kind of looking at.

01:58:40.420 --> 01:58:44.660
[Amit Varma]: But the sense there is, and this is, you know, Ajay has also made this lament in episodes

01:58:44.660 --> 01:58:48.380
[Amit Varma]: that he's done with me, that, you know, at that time, there was like a perfect storm

01:58:48.380 --> 01:58:53.220
[Amit Varma]: in the sense not only was there a crisis, which allowed you to carry these reforms out,

01:58:53.220 --> 01:58:57.740
[Amit Varma]: but there was that intellectual ballast and a community of elites who believed in them

01:58:57.740 --> 01:58:59.300
[Amit Varma]: and who cared about them.

01:58:59.300 --> 01:59:04.740
[Amit Varma]: And Ajay's contention is that that has dissipated, that that is not there anymore.

01:59:04.740 --> 01:59:10.380
[Amit Varma]: So not only has a momentum gone in a political sense, but even that community of thinkers

01:59:10.380 --> 01:59:14.860
[Amit Varma]: who believed in it, the Ashok Desai's of the world, for example, are no longer there.

01:59:14.860 --> 01:59:19.540
[Amit Varma]: Ashok, Monte Kaluwalia, Rakesh Mohan, NK Singh, all of them.

01:59:19.540 --> 01:59:25.580
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, in retrospect, people we can look back and think of as such great figures in history.

01:59:25.580 --> 01:59:30.460
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things Ajay keeps talking about is how we need to build that back, build a

01:59:30.460 --> 01:59:34.220
[Amit Varma]: community of young people who can kind of take that space.

01:59:34.220 --> 01:59:35.220
[Amit Varma]: Different matter.

01:59:35.220 --> 01:59:36.220
[Amit Varma]: Now, couple of things.

01:59:36.220 --> 01:59:41.100
[Amit Varma]: One, therefore, there is the pessimism, because I always have to express pessimism at some

01:59:41.100 --> 01:59:44.460
[Amit Varma]: point that that arc doesn't necessarily go towards freedom.

01:59:44.460 --> 01:59:47.860
[Amit Varma]: And in a social context, I just feel we're in a terrible place and maybe we can come

01:59:47.860 --> 01:59:48.860
[Amit Varma]: to that later.

01:59:48.860 --> 01:59:53.220
[Amit Varma]: But even in the context of what's happening to the economy, it's kind of going downhill.

01:59:53.220 --> 01:59:57.220
[Amit Varma]: But the deeper question there is, and you spoke about Gareebi Hatao and why it is such

01:59:57.220 --> 01:59:59.020
[Amit Varma]: a powerful slogan.

01:59:59.020 --> 02:00:07.380
[Amit Varma]: The deeper thing here is that the truths of economics, that trade is a positive sum game,

02:00:07.380 --> 02:00:11.460
[Amit Varma]: that there is spontaneous order in economies, they don't need to be organized from the top

02:00:11.460 --> 02:00:12.460
[Amit Varma]: down.

02:00:12.460 --> 02:00:16.420
[Amit Varma]: All these deep truths of the way economies work are unintuitive.

02:00:16.420 --> 02:00:19.540
[Amit Varma]: We are wired to think of the world in zero-sum ways.

02:00:19.540 --> 02:00:23.860
[Amit Varma]: We are wired to think of anything that is there to have been built by someone, to have

02:00:23.860 --> 02:00:27.680
[Amit Varma]: been planned by someone, that whole notion of spontaneous order doesn't apply.

02:00:27.680 --> 02:00:33.420
[Amit Varma]: So therefore, it's even though a slogan like Gareebi Hatao is, you know, and when you look

02:00:33.420 --> 02:00:38.660
[Amit Varma]: at the policy she's carrying out is simply nonsense, they are intuitive, and therefore,

02:00:38.660 --> 02:00:44.380
[Amit Varma]: they play into an easy kind of populism, like one of the ways that I think one of the core

02:00:44.380 --> 02:00:49.580
[Amit Varma]: aspects of populism everywhere is that it depends on simplistic narratives.

02:00:49.580 --> 02:00:50.580
[Amit Varma]: Everybody gets it.

02:00:50.580 --> 02:00:51.580
[Amit Varma]: It's simple.

02:00:51.580 --> 02:00:57.660
[Guest]: You know, even when Trump came to power, for example, so his narrative for why jobs are

02:00:57.660 --> 02:01:02.220
[Amit Varma]: going down in Middle America are one, immigrants are coming and taking your jobs, immigration

02:01:02.220 --> 02:01:05.220
[Amit Varma]: bad, and they're shipping your jobs to China, China bad.

02:01:05.220 --> 02:01:07.240
[Amit Varma]: And we know that's not true, right?

02:01:07.240 --> 02:01:09.360
[Amit Varma]: But simplistic narratives sell.

02:01:09.360 --> 02:01:15.200
[Amit Varma]: And even today, my worry, therefore, is that a politician's incentive is always going to

02:01:15.200 --> 02:01:16.720
[Amit Varma]: be the next election.

02:01:16.720 --> 02:01:19.020
[Amit Varma]: He will do what gets him votes.

02:01:19.020 --> 02:01:22.620
[Amit Varma]: And what will get him votes are these populist narratives.

02:01:22.620 --> 02:01:28.860
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, and it almost, if I am to sort of take a darker view than I actually do,

02:01:28.860 --> 02:01:34.540
[Amit Varma]: but I'm perhaps overstating it, it's almost like a lucky accident at 91 could happen that

02:01:34.540 --> 02:01:38.060
[Amit Varma]: those people were there, that that crisis happened.

02:01:38.060 --> 02:01:41.260
[Amit Varma]: And we could lift those 300, 400 million people out of poverty.

02:01:41.260 --> 02:01:45.660
[Amit Varma]: But that line of causation is not sort of easily understood.

02:01:45.660 --> 02:01:47.660
[Guest]: So what's your sense of this?

02:01:47.660 --> 02:01:57.860
[Guest]: So, you know, the argument that I try to make is that reform happens in India by lucky accidents.

02:01:57.860 --> 02:02:01.560
[Guest]: So I like that phrasing.

02:02:01.560 --> 02:02:07.180
[Guest]: But that doesn't mean you can't prepare to take advantage when the lucky accident does

02:02:07.180 --> 02:02:08.300
[Guest]: happen.

02:02:08.300 --> 02:02:14.340
[Guest]: So what is the accident that you need to have come together?

02:02:14.340 --> 02:02:21.820
[Guest]: You need a committed politician, so a minister who wants to get something done, a senior

02:02:21.820 --> 02:02:27.620
[Guest]: bureaucrat, secretary or joint secretaries, at least, who know what needs to be done and

02:02:27.620 --> 02:02:36.420
[Guest]: have the competence and so on to do it, and third, preparation on what needs to be done.

02:02:36.420 --> 02:02:42.940
[Guest]: So my argument is that, say, for example, from CIA, from the Confederation of Indian

02:02:42.940 --> 02:02:47.700
[Guest]: Industry, we should constantly be prepared and ready with the what needs to be done.

02:02:47.700 --> 02:02:49.420
[Guest]: That's within our control.

02:02:49.420 --> 02:02:55.700
[Guest]: Getting the right bureaucrat, getting the right minister is not within our control.

02:02:55.700 --> 02:03:01.460
[Guest]: But when the minister and bureaucrat lines up, we better make sure that that third staff

02:03:01.460 --> 02:03:07.260
[Guest]: being prepared with what needs to be done is ready and available in granular, detailed

02:03:07.260 --> 02:03:08.260
[Guest]: form.

02:03:08.260 --> 02:03:11.900
[Guest]: Because if it is, then suddenly something will move.

02:03:11.900 --> 02:03:17.420
[Guest]: What brings that minister together with that competent bureaucrat is an accident.

02:03:17.420 --> 02:03:20.340
[Guest]: So that's how I think reform happens.

02:03:20.340 --> 02:03:26.180
[Guest]: So I think we had that preparatory work that had happened, you know, the M document from

02:03:26.180 --> 02:03:32.660
[Guest]: Montague and so on, Ashok Desai, you know, with his influence, etc.

02:03:32.660 --> 02:03:37.700
[Guest]: But you had this M document, you had an industrial policy paper that had been worked on by Rakesh

02:03:37.700 --> 02:03:42.620
[Guest]: Mohan, all of this stuff was in place, a lot of contact with CIA, a lot of input from CIA

02:03:42.620 --> 02:03:44.980
[Guest]: at the time and Tarun Das and so on.

02:03:44.980 --> 02:03:47.780
[Guest]: All of this is in place in 1991.

02:03:47.780 --> 02:03:50.500
[Guest]: You then have Manmohan Singh coming in.

02:03:50.500 --> 02:03:52.580
[Guest]: You have Montague as the finance secretary.

02:03:52.580 --> 02:03:55.620
[Guest]: You have Ashok Desai as the chief economic advisor.

02:03:55.620 --> 02:03:56.620
[Guest]: You have N.K.

02:03:56.620 --> 02:03:57.620
[Guest]: Singh as the revenue secretary.

02:03:57.620 --> 02:03:58.620
[Guest]: You have A.N.

02:03:58.620 --> 02:04:00.140
[Guest]: Varma in the PMO.

02:04:00.140 --> 02:04:04.220
[Guest]: You have Rakesh Mohan in the industry ministry, and things happen, right?

02:04:04.220 --> 02:04:11.940
[Guest]: It is this happy accident, but it's a happy accident that only comes to fruit because

02:04:11.940 --> 02:04:14.460
[Guest]: there was that preparation that was in place.

02:04:14.460 --> 02:04:16.860
[Guest]: And I think that's how we have to see reform.

02:04:16.860 --> 02:04:17.920
[Guest]: We have to be ready.

02:04:17.920 --> 02:04:20.740
[Guest]: So on higher education, we need to be clear.

02:04:20.740 --> 02:04:22.180
[Guest]: These are the things that we need to do.

02:04:22.180 --> 02:04:25.100
[Guest]: We need to have policies worked out.

02:04:25.100 --> 02:04:30.500
[Guest]: Same on technology and CSIR and everything else, you know, we should be clear on what

02:04:30.500 --> 02:04:31.580
[Guest]: needs to be done.

02:04:31.580 --> 02:04:36.020
[Guest]: And then if we're lucky enough to get the right minister of science and technology and

02:04:36.020 --> 02:04:38.300
[Guest]: the right secretary DST, we can move.

02:04:38.300 --> 02:04:39.300
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:04:39.300 --> 02:04:43.620
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you mentioned Lincoln earlier, and there's also this quote by Lincoln about how

02:04:43.620 --> 02:04:47.820
[Amit Varma]: if he has five hours to chop down a tree, he'll spend the first four hours sharpening

02:04:47.820 --> 02:04:50.780
[Amit Varma]: the axe, which is kind of what preparation seems like.

02:04:50.780 --> 02:04:51.780
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

02:04:51.780 --> 02:04:54.860
[Amit Varma]: If I am to be a little negative about it and give, you know, come up with another metaphor,

02:04:54.860 --> 02:04:58.620
[Amit Varma]: I would say it's like running into a wall again and again, hoping that at some point

02:04:58.620 --> 02:04:59.620
[Guest]: a door will open.

02:04:59.620 --> 02:05:04.300
[Guest]: That's right, or sometime you hit the door, it will open.

02:05:04.300 --> 02:05:05.780
[Guest]: You have to have that patience.

02:05:05.780 --> 02:05:06.780
[Guest]: You have to have that patience.

02:05:06.780 --> 02:05:11.300
[Guest]: You have to have that patience in our, and you know, if you have that patience, I think

02:05:11.300 --> 02:05:16.460
[Guest]: we've seen things move and reforms happen, which you never thought would be possible.

02:05:16.460 --> 02:05:19.540
[Guest]: I mean, GST is a very good example, right?

02:05:19.540 --> 02:05:25.580
[Guest]: I mean, you know, GST was spoken about for the first time by Yashwant Sinha when he was

02:05:25.580 --> 02:05:32.540
[Guest]: finance minister in the Vajpayee government, then repeated several times by Chidambaram

02:05:32.540 --> 02:05:39.340
[Guest]: in the UPA government, and then it comes back and actually happens under Modi and Jaitley.

02:05:39.340 --> 02:05:42.140
[Amit Varma]: But the implementation was massively botched, I have to say.

02:05:42.140 --> 02:05:43.140
[Guest]: I don't know.

02:05:43.140 --> 02:05:44.220
[Guest]: I agree.

02:05:44.220 --> 02:05:46.900
[Guest]: But at the same time, it took time.

02:05:46.900 --> 02:05:48.060
[Guest]: It took time.

02:05:48.060 --> 02:05:51.940
[Guest]: And the net effect of GST is positive.

02:05:51.940 --> 02:05:55.580
[Guest]: The net, you know, at the end of the day, could GST be better?

02:05:55.580 --> 02:05:56.940
[Guest]: Yes, without question.

02:05:56.940 --> 02:06:01.220
[Guest]: But was GST better than what we had just before GST?

02:06:01.220 --> 02:06:02.780
[Amit Varma]: Hugely better.

02:06:02.780 --> 02:06:06.740
[Amit Varma]: You know, I know small business owners who will actually disagree with that a bit, but

02:06:06.740 --> 02:06:09.740
[Guest]: I, let's not get into the weeds, but.

02:06:09.740 --> 02:06:16.780
[Guest]: No, no, they do because of how cumbersome the formalities are.

02:06:16.780 --> 02:06:23.880
[Guest]: It adds a big regulatory burden, and the fact that you have to do registrations and returns

02:06:23.880 --> 02:06:29.420
[Guest]: in each state in the country is a very stupid thing to have done.

02:06:29.420 --> 02:06:35.820
[Guest]: You know, it got all the states to go along, but it's very onerous in terms of the burden

02:06:35.820 --> 02:06:38.380
[Guest]: it places, especially on small firms.

02:06:38.380 --> 02:06:47.620
[Guest]: So I mean, I take the point, but is it, if you say, is it better than what came before?

02:06:47.620 --> 02:06:52.940
[Guest]: I mean, before, every state had, you see, you had the same requirement.

02:06:52.940 --> 02:06:55.780
[Guest]: You had to file a sales tax return in every state.

02:06:55.780 --> 02:07:00.700
[Guest]: So it was no less burdensome, even for small firms then.

02:07:00.700 --> 02:07:03.780
[Guest]: And you didn't get the offset of input taxes.

02:07:03.780 --> 02:07:06.980
[Amit Varma]: So one of the writers I find most insightful on the subject of the state is, of course,

02:07:06.980 --> 02:07:07.980
[Amit Varma]: Francis Fukuyama.

02:07:07.980 --> 02:07:11.220
[Amit Varma]: He's written those two great books about the history of the state, and he's also written

02:07:11.220 --> 02:07:13.300
[Amit Varma]: a different book on governance.

02:07:13.300 --> 02:07:18.340
[Amit Varma]: And I love the framework he brings to mind when we talk about the state, where he talks

02:07:18.340 --> 02:07:22.300
[Amit Varma]: about the scope and the strength of the state, right?

02:07:22.300 --> 02:07:26.460
[Amit Varma]: Scope being how many things it does and strength being state capacity, how strong it is in

02:07:26.460 --> 02:07:27.460
[Amit Varma]: those.

02:07:27.460 --> 02:07:33.180
[Amit Varma]: And it kind of strikes me that the problem with India is that the scope is too large

02:07:33.180 --> 02:07:34.980
[Amit Varma]: and the strength is too small.

02:07:34.980 --> 02:07:40.100
[Amit Varma]: So we have a weak state that does many things instead of a strong state that does a few

02:07:40.100 --> 02:07:41.820
[Amit Varma]: things but doesn't bloody well.

02:07:41.820 --> 02:07:45.800
[Amit Varma]: You know, things like law and order, defense, and, you know, we kind of agree on that.

02:07:45.800 --> 02:07:49.700
[Amit Varma]: But we have a state that does many things and does them badly.

02:07:49.700 --> 02:07:54.340
[Amit Varma]: Another framework that I find interesting to think about it is James Buchanan's framework

02:07:54.340 --> 02:07:58.780
[Amit Varma]: of looking at the state, where he talks about, on the one hand, a state that is protective

02:07:58.780 --> 02:08:02.940
[Amit Varma]: and productive, and on the other hand, a state that is predatory.

02:08:02.940 --> 02:08:08.140
[Amit Varma]: And states, by their very nature, as public choice theory will tell you, tend to move

02:08:08.140 --> 02:08:12.020
[Amit Varma]: towards a predatory, because power always corrupts.

02:08:12.020 --> 02:08:18.740
[Amit Varma]: And any state will always find ways to accumulate more power to exercise more power.

02:08:18.740 --> 02:08:22.500
[Amit Varma]: Even you've given examples of how during COVID, you know, at one point, I think you mentioned

02:08:22.500 --> 02:08:25.940
[Amit Varma]: something like it takes four hours to call a lockdown and four months to come back from

02:08:25.940 --> 02:08:28.260
[Amit Varma]: it, to get the economy working again.

02:08:28.260 --> 02:08:33.300
[Amit Varma]: And there is a general tendency through history of just states getting more and more powerful.

02:08:33.300 --> 02:08:37.060
[Amit Varma]: And I think in India, you know, I think the rule of law is absent.

02:08:37.060 --> 02:08:41.900
[Amit Varma]: Maybe privileged people like you or me can use our connections and find some kind of

02:08:41.900 --> 02:08:43.500
[Amit Varma]: – but that's not the rule of law.

02:08:43.500 --> 02:08:48.060
[Amit Varma]: For most people in this country, the rule of law is simply absent, especially for the

02:08:48.060 --> 02:08:52.420
[Amit Varma]: underprivileged, if you're Muslim or Dalit or woman or whatever.

02:08:52.420 --> 02:08:55.500
[Amit Varma]: And we are fundamentally a predatory state.

02:08:55.500 --> 02:08:58.540
[Amit Varma]: And that's kind of pretty much all we are.

02:08:58.540 --> 02:09:03.120
[Amit Varma]: And you've spoken at length about this, you know, how we should – I'll read this passage

02:09:03.120 --> 02:09:07.300
[Amit Varma]: out by you where you write, the state should stop doing many, many things, owning the public

02:09:07.300 --> 02:09:11.420
[Amit Varma]: sector banks and insurance companies, fixing pharmaceutical and stent prices, telling colleges

02:09:11.420 --> 02:09:14.500
[Amit Varma]: what fees they should charge, determining if we should stand for the national anthem

02:09:14.500 --> 02:09:17.700
[Amit Varma]: and when it should be played, and dictating whether we can eat beef or not.

02:09:17.700 --> 02:09:21.060
[Amit Varma]: I say this not as an ideological choice, but as a practical proposition.

02:09:21.060 --> 02:09:25.220
[Amit Varma]: If there is one thing I have learned to appreciate of the workings of our government, it is that

02:09:25.220 --> 02:09:28.740
[Amit Varma]: the commitment and knowledge of the highest levels of government, secretaries, additional

02:09:28.740 --> 02:09:32.660
[Amit Varma]: joint secretaries, so on, is matched only by the paucity of talent further down the

02:09:32.660 --> 02:09:33.660
[Amit Varma]: system.

02:09:33.660 --> 02:09:36.460
[Amit Varma]: This means the state has very limited implementation capacity.

02:09:36.460 --> 02:09:39.580
[Amit Varma]: And if we wish to progress, we had better focus on just a few things and get the state

02:09:39.580 --> 02:09:44.340
[Amit Varma]: out of the way for everything else, leaving the rest to India's entrepreneurial energy,

02:09:44.340 --> 02:09:46.580
[Amit Varma]: private enterprise and the market stop good.

02:09:46.580 --> 02:09:51.900
[Amit Varma]: And this is also an argument my friend Ruben Abraham often makes about the opportunity

02:09:51.900 --> 02:09:55.420
[Amit Varma]: cost of state capacity that on the one hand, there is of course, a principled argument

02:09:55.420 --> 02:09:58.780
[Amit Varma]: that the state should only do ABC and not the rest of the alphabet.

02:09:58.780 --> 02:10:03.140
[Amit Varma]: And on the other hand, there is the opportunity cost argument, which you also made eloquently,

02:10:03.140 --> 02:10:08.220
[Amit Varma]: that the state has the capacity to only do three things to do the ones that matter.

02:10:08.220 --> 02:10:10.060
[Amit Varma]: So I wanted to elaborate on this a bit.

02:10:10.060 --> 02:10:14.980
[Amit Varma]: But the larger question that I keep coming to is, how do we ever get there?

02:10:14.980 --> 02:10:17.360
[Amit Varma]: Like is it like you've studied economic history?

02:10:17.360 --> 02:10:22.380
[Amit Varma]: Is there an example of the state actually getting out of the way of getting smaller,

02:10:22.380 --> 02:10:27.700
[Amit Varma]: like apart from a major war or destruction or whatever, like even when say, you know,

02:10:27.700 --> 02:10:32.280
[Amit Varma]: Reagan came to America saying pretty much the same things, you know, what we found was

02:10:32.280 --> 02:10:34.740
[Amit Varma]: that even within him, the state just expanded.

02:10:34.740 --> 02:10:37.220
[Amit Varma]: It's like it was a beast that even he couldn't find.

02:10:37.220 --> 02:10:41.620
[Amit Varma]: And you have this great quote by him and in your book where you said the nine scariest

02:10:41.620 --> 02:10:46.020
[Amit Varma]: words in the English language, I'm from the government and I'm here to help Ronald Reagan

02:10:46.020 --> 02:10:47.020
[Amit Varma]: said that.

02:10:47.020 --> 02:10:51.540
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about this, because it is at one level, it is an ideal and both

02:10:51.540 --> 02:10:53.860
[Amit Varma]: of us would agree that this is our utopia.

02:10:53.860 --> 02:10:58.700
[Amit Varma]: The state does a few things, does them damn well, otherwise it enables and protects civil

02:10:58.700 --> 02:11:00.980
[Amit Varma]: society, which does its own thing.

02:11:00.980 --> 02:11:04.580
[Amit Varma]: But you know, is there movement towards it, is movement towards it possible?

02:11:04.580 --> 02:11:05.700
[Guest]: What is your sense?

02:11:05.700 --> 02:11:11.100
[Guest]: So two examples, one from the UK and one from ourselves.

02:11:11.100 --> 02:11:15.080
[Guest]: So in the UK, Margaret Thatcher is, I think, a great illustration of the state actually

02:11:15.080 --> 02:11:17.820
[Guest]: getting out of doing many, many things.

02:11:17.820 --> 02:11:22.380
[Guest]: You know, privatization, huge privatization program where British Leyland, British Airways,

02:11:22.380 --> 02:11:26.260
[Guest]: British Telecom, all of them get privatized.

02:11:26.260 --> 02:11:35.260
[Guest]: You know, the move away from the state controlling exchange, getting rid of exchange controls,

02:11:35.260 --> 02:11:41.420
[Guest]: getting rid of a whole bunch of things again, right, getting the state out of doing R&D,

02:11:41.420 --> 02:11:46.420
[Guest]: you know, in terms of privatizing what was then called the National Research Development

02:11:46.420 --> 02:11:48.460
[Guest]: Corporation in the UK.

02:11:48.460 --> 02:11:54.700
[Guest]: So I mean, many, many, I think a very significant move away from the state that was sold to

02:11:54.700 --> 02:11:58.380
[Guest]: the public in very popular terms.

02:11:58.380 --> 02:12:02.740
[Guest]: And you know, it comes back to a point that you made earlier on, which is that populist

02:12:02.740 --> 02:12:15.260
[Guest]: rhetoric sometimes can pick simplistic solutions or simplistic policies that are only populist

02:12:15.260 --> 02:12:20.900
[Guest]: and sound good, but don't have any substance and certainly don't have any effect.

02:12:20.900 --> 02:12:29.620
[Guest]: But you can also come up with popular communication that is powerful and pushes reform forward.

02:12:29.620 --> 02:12:34.940
[Guest]: And I think a great example of that is actually what the Thatcher government did in the UK,

02:12:34.940 --> 02:12:41.020
[Guest]: where they hired Saatchi and Saatchi as an ad agency to sell their reform program to

02:12:41.020 --> 02:12:42.020
[Guest]: the public.

02:12:42.020 --> 02:12:47.340
[Guest]: I think probably one of the best investments they made at the time.

02:12:47.340 --> 02:12:55.220
[Guest]: Now, take our own example, post 1991, the state literally became smaller.

02:12:55.220 --> 02:12:58.860
[Guest]: You know, now, OK, it didn't literally become smaller.

02:12:58.860 --> 02:13:02.780
[Guest]: But in relative terms, it certainly became smaller.

02:13:02.780 --> 02:13:10.940
[Guest]: If your metric is government officials or bureaucrats per unit of GDP, the state became

02:13:10.940 --> 02:13:16.660
[Guest]: dramatically smaller between 1991 and 2017.

02:13:16.660 --> 02:13:19.620
[Guest]: And it's maybe something that we should try and measure sometime.

02:13:19.620 --> 02:13:22.080
[Guest]: Maybe I'll try to do it.

02:13:22.080 --> 02:13:26.500
[Guest]: But it became dramatically smaller because the economy took off and the government stayed

02:13:26.500 --> 02:13:27.500
[Guest]: the same size.

02:13:27.500 --> 02:13:31.580
[Guest]: It didn't get smaller, but it didn't get, you know, it didn't keep growing.

02:13:31.580 --> 02:13:34.940
[Guest]: And it got out of doing many, many things.

02:13:34.940 --> 02:13:40.300
[Guest]: Famously, in the 91, 96 period, there were whole government departments that were transferred

02:13:40.300 --> 02:13:44.260
[Guest]: to the railways because the railways were seen as this huge employer.

02:13:44.260 --> 02:13:47.580
[Guest]: And you know, what difference would a few more thousand people make?

02:13:47.580 --> 02:13:55.020
[Guest]: So you know, when DGTD was closed, when MRTP was scrapped, there were many of those agencies

02:13:55.020 --> 02:13:59.260
[Guest]: that were wholesale transferred and some of them were transferred even to the railways

02:13:59.260 --> 02:14:03.500
[Guest]: simply because there was no other place to put them.

02:14:03.500 --> 02:14:04.500
[Amit Varma]: Have you heard of the CCA?

02:14:04.500 --> 02:14:05.500
[Amit Varma]: Well, yes.

02:14:05.500 --> 02:14:09.140
[Amit Varma]: So I'll relate this for my listeners very quickly anyway.

02:14:09.140 --> 02:14:10.900
[Amit Varma]: No, but I don't know what happened with them.

02:14:10.900 --> 02:14:11.900
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:14:11.900 --> 02:14:18.540
[Amit Varma]: So basically, in 1984, this bureaucrat somewhere got an application from this department of

02:14:18.540 --> 02:14:22.780
[Amit Varma]: the Tamil Nadu government asking for an increase in their budget.

02:14:22.780 --> 02:14:24.780
[Amit Varma]: And this department was called CCA.

02:14:24.780 --> 02:14:25.780
[Guest]: So he decided to look into...

02:14:25.780 --> 02:14:26.780
[Guest]: No, no.

02:14:26.780 --> 02:14:27.780
[Guest]: I haven't heard of the CCA.

02:14:27.780 --> 02:14:28.780
[Amit Varma]: You haven't heard of this one?

02:14:28.780 --> 02:14:29.780
[Amit Varma]: Oh, okay.

02:14:29.780 --> 02:14:31.020
[Amit Varma]: So this department was called the CCA.

02:14:31.020 --> 02:14:34.420
[Amit Varma]: So he decided to look into it that they've asked for an increase in their budget.

02:14:34.420 --> 02:14:36.280
[Amit Varma]: I think it's about 83, 84.

02:14:36.280 --> 02:14:39.380
[Amit Varma]: And so what, you know, what is this department?

02:14:39.380 --> 02:14:41.500
[Amit Varma]: So then he goes back into the history of it.

02:14:41.500 --> 02:14:47.300
[Amit Varma]: And the history of it is this, that Winston Churchill used to be a fan of cigars, right?

02:14:47.300 --> 02:14:49.320
[Amit Varma]: And then World War Two breaks out.

02:14:49.320 --> 02:14:53.860
[Amit Varma]: And all his cigars, they were coming from Cuba, because of course, he's an aficionado

02:14:53.860 --> 02:14:55.780
[Amit Varma]: and that's where the best cigars come from.

02:14:55.780 --> 02:14:59.300
[Amit Varma]: But that trade route closes down because of World War Two and he can no longer get his

02:14:59.300 --> 02:15:00.300
[Amit Varma]: cigars from there.

02:15:00.300 --> 02:15:03.260
[Amit Varma]: Now, he's got to have his cigars because remember, he's saving the Western world.

02:15:03.260 --> 02:15:04.300
[Amit Varma]: So what does he do?

02:15:04.300 --> 02:15:09.260
[Amit Varma]: The second best cigars in the world apparently were a place near Chennai called...

02:15:09.260 --> 02:15:11.060
[Amit Varma]: I've forgotten the name.

02:15:11.060 --> 02:15:13.180
[Amit Varma]: It starts with T and it's a very long name.

02:15:13.180 --> 02:15:14.180
[Amit Varma]: Apologies.

02:15:14.180 --> 02:15:18.900
[Amit Varma]: I'm not dissing Tamilians, but Tiruchirappalli or something like that, right?

02:15:18.900 --> 02:15:24.200
[Amit Varma]: So a department is set up in the colonial government of India to get those cigars across

02:15:24.200 --> 02:15:25.680
[Amit Varma]: to him during the war.

02:15:25.680 --> 02:15:31.180
[Amit Varma]: And the department is called CCA Churchill Cigar Assistant, right?

02:15:31.180 --> 02:15:37.220
[Amit Varma]: So World War Two ends, India becomes independent, Churchill dies, and till 1984, this department

02:15:37.220 --> 02:15:38.280
[Amit Varma]: is running.

02:15:38.280 --> 02:15:42.600
[Amit Varma]: And then they actually have the audacity to apply for an increase in their budget.

02:15:42.600 --> 02:15:50.700
[Amit Varma]: And this to me is sort of a classic illustration of how it is so hard to downsize the state.

02:15:50.700 --> 02:15:54.660
[Amit Varma]: But you know, again, I'll quote from what you say about the 91 reforms and how they

02:15:54.660 --> 02:15:58.660
[Amit Varma]: did actually, in a sense, downsize state, where you write, quote, I have long held the

02:15:58.660 --> 02:16:02.560
[Amit Varma]: view that we should not seek better government, we should seek less government.

02:16:02.560 --> 02:16:04.900
[Amit Varma]: That is my reading of the 1991 reforms.

02:16:04.900 --> 02:16:09.820
[Amit Varma]: The state retreated from industrial licensing, control of foreign investment, public sector

02:16:09.820 --> 02:16:14.340
[Amit Varma]: monopolies and everything from airlines to steel, and opened up to in imports.

02:16:14.340 --> 02:16:19.960
[Amit Varma]: The resultant jump in growth multiplied our GDP eight times from 340 billion in 1991 to

02:16:19.960 --> 02:16:22.780
[Amit Varma]: 2650 billion in 2017.

02:16:22.780 --> 02:16:27.340
[Amit Varma]: It is only in the last four years that we have seen growth sag, and, stop quote, and

02:16:27.340 --> 02:16:28.340
[Amit Varma]: so on.

02:16:28.340 --> 02:16:32.500
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, when we say less government, when I say less government, I'm thinking of

02:16:32.500 --> 02:16:34.000
[Amit Varma]: the predatory state.

02:16:34.000 --> 02:16:39.800
[Amit Varma]: If it feeds upon us less, we'll have more space and more energy to actually do things.

02:16:39.800 --> 02:16:43.580
[Amit Varma]: People often represent it as, oh, who will look after the poor then, or we need the state

02:16:43.580 --> 02:16:44.580
[Amit Varma]: or whatever.

02:16:44.580 --> 02:16:48.300
[Amit Varma]: But look at what the state is actually doing in the role that it plays in our lives.

02:16:48.300 --> 02:16:51.680
[Amit Varma]: So the state in India is largely kind of predatory.

02:16:51.680 --> 02:16:55.880
[Amit Varma]: At one point, for example, during COVID, you've written here about how your company was coping

02:16:55.880 --> 02:16:58.700
[Amit Varma]: and you wrote, quote, we need passes for everything.

02:16:58.700 --> 02:17:02.740
[Amit Varma]: We need a pass to bring people to work, a pass to source packing material, a pass to

02:17:02.740 --> 02:17:07.580
[Amit Varma]: get the logistics providers in, another pass to get a truck in and on its way to the customer.

02:17:07.580 --> 02:17:12.540
[Amit Varma]: Each takes time and is variably interpreted by each individual policeman, stop quote.

02:17:12.540 --> 02:17:16.100
[Amit Varma]: And in episode 250 of the show, one of my friends was a small, you know, who runs a

02:17:16.100 --> 02:17:20.760
[Amit Varma]: small factory in Narain, Chennai had also kind of spoken about this.

02:17:20.760 --> 02:17:24.500
[Amit Varma]: And much as licensing went, we did some reforms in 91.

02:17:24.500 --> 02:17:29.140
[Amit Varma]: But like in 2009, for example, I read about the Four Seasons Hotel opening in Bombay,

02:17:29.140 --> 02:17:34.180
[Amit Varma]: where they needed 165 licenses to open, 165.

02:17:34.180 --> 02:17:38.140
[Amit Varma]: And of which two were for different weighing machines, one for the kitchen and one for

02:17:38.140 --> 02:17:39.140
[Amit Varma]: each room.

02:17:39.140 --> 02:17:40.140
[Amit Varma]: Right.

02:17:40.140 --> 02:17:42.220
[Amit Varma]: So there was still so many reforms pending.

02:17:42.220 --> 02:17:47.620
[Amit Varma]: And I think just seeing the massive impact of the limited reforms, I think some of us

02:17:47.620 --> 02:17:49.700
[Amit Varma]: started celebrating too soon.

02:17:49.700 --> 02:17:53.020
[Amit Varma]: And there is still kind of so much work to be done.

02:17:53.020 --> 02:18:00.220
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about the fundamental reforms that 91 did not tackle.

02:18:00.220 --> 02:18:06.100
[Guest]: Sure, so the 91 reforms, you know, that list covers what it did tackle.

02:18:06.100 --> 02:18:07.100
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:18:07.100 --> 02:18:08.100
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:18:08.100 --> 02:18:09.100
[Guest]: And it's well known.

02:18:09.100 --> 02:18:12.780
[Guest]: What were the areas that were the big areas that I think were untouched?

02:18:12.780 --> 02:18:15.700
[Guest]: We did not touch education, right?

02:18:15.700 --> 02:18:19.020
[Guest]: So huge area, if you ask me, both school and college education.

02:18:19.020 --> 02:18:24.660
[Guest]: Now, you can make some argument that school is a, you know, a joint subject between both

02:18:24.660 --> 02:18:27.460
[Guest]: union and states, so, you know, okay.

02:18:27.460 --> 02:18:29.460
[Guest]: So it needed to take the states along.

02:18:29.460 --> 02:18:32.980
[Guest]: But higher education is largely union, could have been addressed.

02:18:32.980 --> 02:18:38.580
[Guest]: We did not address the role of technology and technology policy in 1991.

02:18:38.580 --> 02:18:48.340
[Guest]: We did not address how bureaucrats are recruited, promoted, rewarded, given feedback, assessed.

02:18:48.340 --> 02:18:52.020
[Guest]: Same mechanisms existed there.

02:18:52.020 --> 02:18:58.020
[Guest]: And we did not really address the question of union state relations.

02:18:58.020 --> 02:19:06.220
[Guest]: Some of that emerged a bit later on, but in somewhat fragmented ways.

02:19:06.220 --> 02:19:09.820
[Guest]: Those are some of the bigger areas that we did not address.

02:19:09.820 --> 02:19:14.220
[Guest]: One thing that we did address, of course, much later is the indirect tax system with

02:19:14.220 --> 02:19:16.140
[Guest]: GST, right?

02:19:16.140 --> 02:19:20.300
[Guest]: So that was not initially addressed, but came much later.

02:19:20.300 --> 02:19:25.580
[Guest]: Another area that was not addressed was labor reform, which was, if you may remember that

02:19:25.580 --> 02:19:30.780
[Guest]: Manmohan Singh spoke about it, as finance minister, it was called an exit policy.

02:19:30.780 --> 02:19:33.900
[Guest]: It was a terribly named policy.

02:19:33.900 --> 02:19:38.140
[Guest]: And the moment it was talked about, there was so much opposition from within the Congress

02:19:38.140 --> 02:19:41.740
[Guest]: government itself that it was immediately killed.

02:19:41.740 --> 02:19:46.540
[Guest]: And then it only came back actually under the current government in 2014.

02:19:46.540 --> 02:19:52.600
[Guest]: And finally, you know, two years ago, we saw these 44 regulation labor laws get turned

02:19:52.600 --> 02:19:54.300
[Guest]: into four labor laws.

02:19:54.300 --> 02:19:57.580
[Guest]: A step in the right direction, but it's a step.

02:19:57.580 --> 02:20:00.580
[Guest]: There's more still that needs to be done.

02:20:00.580 --> 02:20:02.940
[Guest]: And then agriculture.

02:20:02.940 --> 02:20:05.060
[Guest]: Agriculture has hardly been touched.

02:20:05.060 --> 02:20:08.940
[Guest]: And the farm laws, in that sense, I think the farm laws were done wrong, and they were

02:20:08.940 --> 02:20:13.140
[Guest]: done without institutional proprietories in place.

02:20:13.140 --> 02:20:19.860
[Guest]: But the objective was right, and the direction of the laws were actually right for actually

02:20:19.860 --> 02:20:22.300
[Guest]: helping agriculture in the country.

02:20:22.300 --> 02:20:30.060
[Guest]: The other area is agricultural taxation, which everyone sees as this, you know, this complete

02:20:30.060 --> 02:20:32.180
[Guest]: holy cow that you can't touch.

02:20:32.180 --> 02:20:34.140
[Guest]: And I've never understood why.

02:20:34.140 --> 02:20:37.860
[Guest]: Because I mean, you can at least start by saying that, listen, you know, let's tax agricultural

02:20:37.860 --> 02:20:38.860
[Guest]: income.

02:20:38.860 --> 02:20:39.860
[Guest]: Let's start at a high level.

02:20:39.860 --> 02:20:42.180
[Guest]: Let's start at one crore a year, you know.

02:20:42.180 --> 02:20:48.120
[Guest]: So tax agricultural incomes over one crore a year to begin with, you know, how can anyone

02:20:48.120 --> 02:20:49.120
[Guest]: object to that?

02:20:49.120 --> 02:20:51.220
[Amit Varma]: Couldn't agree with you more about the farm bills.

02:20:51.220 --> 02:20:56.100
[Amit Varma]: In fact, Ajay Shah and I did an episode called the tragedy of the farm bills, which is which

02:20:56.100 --> 02:20:59.700
[Amit Varma]: I'll link again from the show notes, talking of the labor laws.

02:20:59.700 --> 02:21:03.340
[Amit Varma]: Now remember, when the labor reforms happened a couple of years back, because they came

02:21:03.340 --> 02:21:07.300
[Amit Varma]: from this government, which I oppose as much as anyone, but because they came from this

02:21:07.300 --> 02:21:12.180
[Amit Varma]: government, there was a loud outcry against them from people who hadn't even thought about

02:21:12.180 --> 02:21:16.700
[Amit Varma]: them or, you know, and they were all like, who will look after the rights of the workers

02:21:16.700 --> 02:21:20.940
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, again, conflating intention with outcome, you know, which is the most

02:21:20.940 --> 02:21:26.220
[Amit Varma]: common mistake people often make when thinking about policy and economics, that, you know,

02:21:26.220 --> 02:21:27.940
[Amit Varma]: we mistake intention for outcome.

02:21:27.940 --> 02:21:32.340
[Amit Varma]: And in this case, you might imagine all the labor laws, the intention is to help workers,

02:21:32.340 --> 02:21:35.060
[Amit Varma]: but actually, they hurt workers much more, exactly.

02:21:35.060 --> 02:21:40.660
[Amit Varma]: And they hurt workers much more because it prevented that explosion in labor intensive

02:21:40.660 --> 02:21:45.700
[Amit Varma]: manufacture would which would have taken India so much further ahead, you know, and that

02:21:45.700 --> 02:21:47.220
[Amit Varma]: was a route China actually took.

02:21:47.220 --> 02:21:51.540
[Amit Varma]: And now that China has, you know, elevated themselves so much, that kind of low cost

02:21:51.540 --> 02:21:55.780
[Amit Varma]: work is actually, as you pointed out, shifting from China to places like Bangladesh and Vietnam,

02:21:55.780 --> 02:21:57.740
[Amit Varma]: and we are still missing the boat.

02:21:57.740 --> 02:22:00.980
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about this.

02:22:00.980 --> 02:22:05.580
[Amit Varma]: Why is shifting to manufacturing jobs so important for an economy?

02:22:05.580 --> 02:22:10.060
[Amit Varma]: What are the kind of different laws that ensure that it did not happen in India?

02:22:10.060 --> 02:22:11.460
[Amit Varma]: And why are we still stuck?

02:22:11.460 --> 02:22:13.420
[Amit Varma]: And is it too late?

02:22:13.420 --> 02:22:19.540
[Guest]: So it, you know, first, the reason manufacturing is so important for all developing countries,

02:22:19.540 --> 02:22:26.500
[Guest]: you know, is that it's the only high quality job that's available in abundance on mass

02:22:26.500 --> 02:22:31.540
[Guest]: scale for people of low skills.

02:22:31.540 --> 02:22:32.820
[Guest]: So that's the thing.

02:22:32.820 --> 02:22:38.380
[Guest]: That's the single reason, right, that you have good quality jobs available on a mass

02:22:38.380 --> 02:22:41.500
[Guest]: scale for people with low skills.

02:22:41.500 --> 02:22:44.140
[Guest]: Now what do I mean by good quality job?

02:22:44.140 --> 02:22:50.500
[Guest]: Good quality job is one where, which is higher productivity to start with, and where you

02:22:50.500 --> 02:22:55.100
[Guest]: have the ability to keep raising productivity on a consistent basis.

02:22:55.100 --> 02:22:57.340
[Guest]: And we know how to do that for manufacturing.

02:22:57.340 --> 02:23:02.820
[Guest]: We've been learning more and more and more for 200 years how to keep improving productivity

02:23:02.820 --> 02:23:03.820
[Guest]: in manufacturing.

02:23:03.820 --> 02:23:08.140
[Guest]: So we know how to grow productivity in manufacturing in the long run.

02:23:08.140 --> 02:23:14.500
[Guest]: And that makes manufacturing jobs a good quality kind of job.

02:23:14.500 --> 02:23:17.340
[Guest]: Now what does it give you?

02:23:17.340 --> 02:23:22.860
[Guest]: If you move people from, the archetype is you move people from sort of marginal productivity

02:23:22.860 --> 02:23:30.340
[Guest]: in agriculture to employment in a factory, you get a jump, a massive jump in productivity.

02:23:30.340 --> 02:23:33.540
[Guest]: I think the Indian multiple is 20.

02:23:33.540 --> 02:23:39.340
[Guest]: So someone working in the modern manufacturing sector is 20 times more productive than the

02:23:39.340 --> 02:23:41.380
[Guest]: average person working in agriculture.

02:23:41.380 --> 02:23:44.900
[Guest]: So average agriculture, average in manufacturing.

02:23:44.900 --> 02:23:47.440
[Guest]: It's a huge jump.

02:23:47.440 --> 02:23:51.180
[Guest]: And then you have the ability to keep growing that productivity of the manufacturing job

02:23:51.180 --> 02:23:52.180
[Guest]: going forward.

02:23:52.180 --> 02:23:58.700
[Guest]: So you have the ability to keep raising incomes, et cetera, in that level.

02:23:58.700 --> 02:24:02.060
[Guest]: Now we have 30 million manufacturing jobs in India.

02:24:02.060 --> 02:24:04.900
[Guest]: But a workforce of 400 million.

02:24:04.900 --> 02:24:05.900
[Guest]: It's a tiny number.

02:24:05.900 --> 02:24:13.220
[Guest]: If you take Bangladesh, Bangladesh has many more, not in absolute terms, but they're much

02:24:13.220 --> 02:24:14.220
[Guest]: smaller.

02:24:14.220 --> 02:24:20.440
[Guest]: Their population of 200 million on our 1,400 million, they're one seventh our size.

02:24:20.440 --> 02:24:22.540
[Guest]: They have manufacturing jobs.

02:24:22.540 --> 02:24:27.140
[Guest]: Manufacturing is a much larger share of their workforce than it is for us.

02:24:27.140 --> 02:24:34.280
[Guest]: And within that manufacturing workforce, many more women work because they have the specialization

02:24:34.280 --> 02:24:35.880
[Guest]: in garment industry.

02:24:35.880 --> 02:24:45.700
[Guest]: So 40% of their garment industry, 40% of their labor force is employed in the garment industry.

02:24:45.700 --> 02:24:47.980
[Guest]: And a majority of them are women.

02:24:47.980 --> 02:24:53.380
[Guest]: And as a result, Bangladesh has a much higher female labor force participation than we do.

02:24:53.380 --> 02:25:01.060
[Guest]: We have the world's lowest female labor force participation ratio out of the top 20 economies,

02:25:01.060 --> 02:25:02.540
[Guest]: the G20.

02:25:02.540 --> 02:25:07.300
[Guest]: So for all those reasons, manufacturing makes a lot of sense for us.

02:25:07.300 --> 02:25:12.980
[Guest]: Now what holds us back from having more manufacturing and labor-intensive manufacturing?

02:25:12.980 --> 02:25:18.960
[Guest]: Decades if you like of legacy from the labor regulations and the way they were enforced.

02:25:18.960 --> 02:25:26.940
[Guest]: For decades, if a case went to court, by and large, the decision would be in favor of labor,

02:25:26.940 --> 02:25:28.780
[Guest]: by and large.

02:25:28.780 --> 02:25:32.420
[Guest]: To close a factory, you needed permission from the government.

02:25:32.420 --> 02:25:33.980
[Guest]: The government wouldn't give permission.

02:25:33.980 --> 02:25:38.460
[Guest]: Instead, they would tell you that, listen, don't pay your electricity bill.

02:25:38.460 --> 02:25:41.080
[Guest]: If you don't pay your electricity bill, they'll cut off the power.

02:25:41.080 --> 02:25:44.340
[Guest]: When they cut off the power, then you can claim that since my power's been cut off,

02:25:44.340 --> 02:25:45.340
[Guest]: I have to close.

02:25:45.340 --> 02:25:50.820
[Guest]: I mean, you find all these weird sort of long way around, scratch my left ear with my right

02:25:50.820 --> 02:25:53.860
[Guest]: hand kind of approaches.

02:25:53.860 --> 02:25:55.700
[Guest]: And it was long pending.

02:25:55.700 --> 02:26:01.400
[Guest]: And as a result, there was this mindset that developed in Indian industry that more labor

02:26:01.400 --> 02:26:02.800
[Guest]: was bad.

02:26:02.800 --> 02:26:05.580
[Guest]: And I think that mindset is still very strong.

02:26:05.580 --> 02:26:12.720
[Guest]: It's still there in industry that we do not see employing more labor as the right thing

02:26:12.720 --> 02:26:15.720
[Guest]: to do for our own growth going forward.

02:26:15.720 --> 02:26:18.940
[Guest]: You see, you want to minimize the amount of labor that you employ.

02:26:18.940 --> 02:26:24.500
[Guest]: It's exactly the contrary impulse that a country like ours needs.

02:26:24.500 --> 02:26:27.640
[Guest]: So that mindset will take time to change.

02:26:27.640 --> 02:26:28.800
[Guest]: How will it change?

02:26:28.800 --> 02:26:35.060
[Guest]: It will change, as I say, these four labor laws that we've now seen is a good step forward.

02:26:35.060 --> 02:26:36.840
[Guest]: But it's a step forward.

02:26:36.840 --> 02:26:41.380
[Guest]: And we have to stick with them for a period of time and get people used to a new way of

02:26:41.380 --> 02:26:47.940
[Guest]: working and then keep moving forward in the direction of labor reform for a long period

02:26:47.940 --> 02:26:54.460
[Guest]: of time before it will start showing up in people starting to say, listen, employing

02:26:54.460 --> 02:26:59.100
[Guest]: a lot of labor is a good way to do business in the country.

02:26:59.100 --> 02:27:00.580
[Guest]: There's a second thing that we can do.

02:27:00.580 --> 02:27:06.460
[Guest]: I think we should actively seek some of the big labor intensive manufacturers to set up

02:27:06.460 --> 02:27:07.460
[Guest]: in India.

02:27:07.460 --> 02:27:12.540
[Guest]: I think the work that's been done to get Foxconn to come into India is a very sensible thing.

02:27:12.540 --> 02:27:15.700
[Guest]: Because they're highly labor intensive.

02:27:15.700 --> 02:27:19.460
[Guest]: They employ largest factory in China.

02:27:19.460 --> 02:27:25.380
[Guest]: I talk about as 400,000 people working in it, one factory making iPhones.

02:27:25.380 --> 02:27:27.700
[Guest]: We need those kinds of factories in India.

02:27:27.700 --> 02:27:33.980
[Guest]: Lee and Fung, they employ hundreds of thousands of people in China making garments.

02:27:33.980 --> 02:27:38.100
[Guest]: We need to find ways in which we can attract them to set up these large plants in India

02:27:38.100 --> 02:27:39.740
[Guest]: as well.

02:27:39.740 --> 02:27:46.180
[Guest]: And then maybe with the power of a few of those examples, more Indian industrialists

02:27:46.180 --> 02:27:51.500
[Guest]: will start saying, listen, yes, a way in which I can progress, I can set up an enterprise

02:27:51.500 --> 02:27:54.520
[Guest]: that can be highly successful that's very labor intensive.

02:27:54.520 --> 02:27:59.020
[Guest]: And then labor intensive manufacturing can start becoming an attractive option.

02:27:59.020 --> 02:28:04.260
[Guest]: We have everything that it takes, I think, but the mindset will need to shift very substantially

02:28:04.260 --> 02:28:10.060
[Guest]: because we have to make up for 50 years of history, literally 50 years of history.

02:28:10.060 --> 02:28:11.060
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:28:11.060 --> 02:28:15.100
[Amit Varma]: And adding to all those legacy labor laws, which this incentivize companies from growing

02:28:15.100 --> 02:28:17.620
[Amit Varma]: too big, because you don't want to hire too many people.

02:28:17.620 --> 02:28:22.460
[Amit Varma]: Adding to that were also a whole bunch of other laws, like, for example, you still aren't

02:28:22.460 --> 02:28:25.940
[Amit Varma]: allowed to sell agricultural land for non agricultural purposes.

02:28:25.940 --> 02:28:31.060
[Amit Varma]: So a typical move away where one farming gets much more productive, and then many farms

02:28:31.060 --> 02:28:35.860
[Amit Varma]: which are struggling to kind of get by, you sell the land, factories are set up, and those

02:28:35.860 --> 02:28:37.580
[Amit Varma]: factories employ many people.

02:28:37.580 --> 02:28:42.820
[Amit Varma]: And that's how economies grow, like everywhere else in the world, the agriculture will perhaps

02:28:42.820 --> 02:28:47.780
[Amit Varma]: employ, you know, employ five to 6% of people in developed countries like the US and India.

02:28:47.780 --> 02:28:51.780
[Amit Varma]: It's, you know, hovering somewhere between 40 to 60 exact figures are hard to come by

02:28:51.780 --> 02:28:53.820
[Amit Varma]: because informal sector and all that.

02:28:53.820 --> 02:28:54.820
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:28:54.820 --> 02:28:55.820
[Guest]: 120 million.

02:28:55.820 --> 02:28:58.380
[Guest]: And we don't need 120 million people in agriculture.

02:28:58.380 --> 02:28:59.380
[Guest]: We don't.

02:28:59.380 --> 02:29:04.500
[Guest]: And in fact, you know, after the, during the pandemic, with the reverse migration that

02:29:04.500 --> 02:29:09.660
[Guest]: took place, 10 million people moved into agriculture, we grew our agricultural labor force.

02:29:09.660 --> 02:29:16.180
[Guest]: I mean, CMI shows that the agricultural number of people employed in agriculture grew.

02:29:16.180 --> 02:29:19.380
[Guest]: That's a damning statement for a country like ours.

02:29:19.380 --> 02:29:20.380
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:29:20.380 --> 02:29:24.660
[Amit Varma]: And I remember in an election a while back, I don't remember which election, but Yogendra

02:29:24.660 --> 02:29:30.060
[Amit Varma]: Yadav made a statement to the effect of that, you know, if farmers have to go and join factories,

02:29:30.060 --> 02:29:33.820
[Amit Varma]: I'm telling you, I will not allow it, which is such a bizarre way of thinking because

02:29:33.820 --> 02:29:40.380
[Guest]: you're romanticizing a life which is nasty, brutish and short, as Hobbes would have said.

02:29:40.380 --> 02:29:46.260
[Amit Varma]: And you are denying them that path to progress, like, you know, when people talk about how

02:29:46.260 --> 02:29:50.540
[Amit Varma]: tough factory jobs are, or, oh, this is a sweatshop, or, oh, what is the labor here?

02:29:50.540 --> 02:29:54.400
[Amit Varma]: The point that they're forgetting is that the people who voluntarily take up those jobs

02:29:54.400 --> 02:29:57.380
[Amit Varma]: are taking it up because it is the best option open to them.

02:29:57.380 --> 02:30:00.580
[Amit Varma]: And you close that option off, they are getting into something much worse.

02:30:00.580 --> 02:30:01.580
[Guest]: I mean, exactly.

02:30:01.580 --> 02:30:05.460
[Guest]: And, you know, and it's actually not getting into something, they're coming from something

02:30:05.460 --> 02:30:06.460
[Guest]: much worse.

02:30:06.460 --> 02:30:07.460
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, exactly.

02:30:07.460 --> 02:30:08.460
[Amit Varma]: They're coming from something much worse.

02:30:08.460 --> 02:30:14.780
[Guest]: And, you know, and by, I mean, we may have all of these, I can understand, you have all

02:30:14.780 --> 02:30:20.380
[Guest]: these principled ideas about, you know, we must have really safe working, yes, we must

02:30:20.380 --> 02:30:23.340
[Guest]: really look after everyone in factories, all of that, yes.

02:30:23.340 --> 02:30:26.460
[Guest]: I mean, you know, I understand the instinct.

02:30:26.460 --> 02:30:33.540
[Guest]: But give people the choice, let people, give people the choice to move out of agriculture

02:30:33.540 --> 02:30:41.380
[Guest]: into jobs in factories, even if they aren't the kind of jobs that we see as being desirable

02:30:41.380 --> 02:30:48.960
[Guest]: and high quality and, you know, of somehow of, you know, that would have all of the support

02:30:48.960 --> 02:30:56.180
[Guest]: mechanisms that we would like to see as being a civilized kind of employment, you know,

02:30:56.180 --> 02:31:01.340
[Guest]: give people those options, people in Bangladesh have that option, our people should have it

02:31:01.340 --> 02:31:02.340
[Amit Varma]: too.

02:31:02.340 --> 02:31:03.340
[Amit Varma]: You're mentioning Bangladesh.

02:31:03.340 --> 02:31:07.460
[Amit Varma]: I remember this study by Oxfam many years ago, where, you know, they wrote about how

02:31:07.460 --> 02:31:12.740
[Amit Varma]: international outrage forced factories to lay off 30,000 child workers, right?

02:31:12.740 --> 02:31:14.780
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, child labor is horrible.

02:31:14.780 --> 02:31:19.000
[Amit Varma]: But what happened, many of those kids starved to death, many became prostitutes.

02:31:19.000 --> 02:31:24.480
[Amit Varma]: And a similar study in 1995, UNICEF studied how an international boycott of carpets made

02:31:24.480 --> 02:31:30.380
[Amit Varma]: in Nepal, again by child labor, led to between 5,000 to 7,000 Nepali girls turning to prostitution

02:31:30.380 --> 02:31:32.780
[Amit Varma]: because a better option was denied to them.

02:31:32.780 --> 02:31:38.500
[Guest]: So I mean, you know, and, you know, I don't think either of us is trying to make an argument

02:31:38.500 --> 02:31:43.860
[Guest]: in favor of child labor, you know, or sweatshops, or any of that.

02:31:43.860 --> 02:31:48.100
[Guest]: But I'm just saying that, you know, it's you have to look at where people are coming from.

02:31:48.100 --> 02:31:51.180
[Guest]: And you know, let people get into these new jobs.

02:31:51.180 --> 02:31:56.060
[Guest]: And when they get into these new factory jobs, then also in Bangladesh, what have we seen

02:31:56.060 --> 02:32:00.540
[Guest]: in the last 10 years, we've seen the safety levels improve dramatically.

02:32:00.540 --> 02:32:01.540
[Guest]: Why?

02:32:01.540 --> 02:32:06.260
[Guest]: Because of demanding buyers that say, hey, listen, you know, you can't buy your garments

02:32:06.260 --> 02:32:11.220
[Guest]: from factories where people are, you know, where they may die in a fire, if a small fire

02:32:11.220 --> 02:32:14.860
[Guest]: breaks out, and it spreads through the whole building, and they don't have safe exits,

02:32:14.860 --> 02:32:16.260
[Guest]: and so on.

02:32:16.260 --> 02:32:17.660
[Guest]: Get things sorted out.

02:32:17.660 --> 02:32:19.820
[Guest]: And people have been getting them sorted out.

02:32:19.820 --> 02:32:22.580
[Amit Varma]: So it's the jobs are improving in quality.

02:32:22.580 --> 02:32:23.580
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

02:32:23.580 --> 02:32:27.660
[Amit Varma]: Like in China as well, where, you know, they've climbed so far of the value chain that a lot

02:32:27.660 --> 02:32:31.740
[Amit Varma]: of these are now leaving and going to Bangladesh and Vietnam, and we are still behind and yes,

02:32:31.740 --> 02:32:33.500
[Amit Varma]: you know, all of that.

02:32:33.500 --> 02:32:36.900
[Amit Varma]: One of the truly thought provoking parts of your book, which made me I mean, all of it

02:32:36.900 --> 02:32:39.340
[Amit Varma]: is thought provoking, but a lot of it I'm familiar with.

02:32:39.340 --> 02:32:44.700
[Amit Varma]: But a part that I was that made me think for the first time, was sort of the way you define

02:32:44.700 --> 02:32:47.260
[Amit Varma]: modernity and the role of the factory in it.

02:32:47.260 --> 02:32:52.740
[Amit Varma]: So at one point, you write, quote, as a society modernizes, people adopt more modern attitudes.

02:32:52.740 --> 02:32:58.380
[Amit Varma]: These include a sense of personal efficacy, openness to new experience, respect for science

02:32:58.380 --> 02:33:02.860
[Amit Varma]: and technology, acceptance of the need for strict scheduling of time, and a positive

02:33:02.860 --> 02:33:06.900
[Amit Varma]: orientation towards planning ahead, stop quote, and all things that you can, you know, get

02:33:06.900 --> 02:33:10.820
[Amit Varma]: from a productivity video on YouTube from Ali Abdaal or Thomas Frank.

02:33:10.820 --> 02:33:17.220
[Amit Varma]: And then you quote Alex Inkels, his book Becoming Modern, where he points out that the two key

02:33:17.220 --> 02:33:20.340
[Amit Varma]: sources of modernity are the school and the factory.

02:33:20.340 --> 02:33:24.620
[Amit Varma]: Now the school everyone can understand, tell me about the role of the factory in this.

02:33:24.620 --> 02:33:31.420
[Guest]: So the factory, the reason, you know, Alex did this study in six countries in the 60s,

02:33:31.420 --> 02:33:36.260
[Guest]: one of the countries being India, and one of them being actually at that time, East

02:33:36.260 --> 02:33:38.060
[Guest]: Pakistan or Bangladesh.

02:33:38.060 --> 02:33:44.780
[Guest]: And when he did that study, he put the scale together as a kind of universal scale of modernity.

02:33:44.780 --> 02:33:46.940
[Guest]: And that was his argument.

02:33:46.940 --> 02:33:53.860
[Guest]: And then looked at all those attributes, and he showed how people who'd been to school

02:33:53.860 --> 02:33:59.100
[Guest]: and been to school for a certain number of years moved more up that scale, and people

02:33:59.100 --> 02:34:02.580
[Guest]: who worked in a factory move more up that scale.

02:34:02.580 --> 02:34:03.660
[Guest]: So why a factory?

02:34:03.660 --> 02:34:06.220
[Guest]: Why is the factory a school for modernity?

02:34:06.220 --> 02:34:11.500
[Guest]: It's a school for modernity because, you know, if you think of it, you come to work from

02:34:11.500 --> 02:34:14.820
[Guest]: time A to time B. So you work to a schedule.

02:34:14.820 --> 02:34:18.540
[Guest]: You learn that if you follow a particular process, you can be more productive.

02:34:18.540 --> 02:34:24.140
[Guest]: If you can be more productive, then you can earn more as a result.

02:34:24.140 --> 02:34:30.780
[Guest]: Third, if you use tools, technology, you can be more productive again, or it involves less

02:34:30.780 --> 02:34:32.140
[Guest]: physical labor.

02:34:32.140 --> 02:34:36.540
[Guest]: So you start gaining a respect for technology and science and so on.

02:34:36.540 --> 02:34:44.740
[Guest]: Fourth, you learn to believe in your own ability to deliver your own destiny instead of someone

02:34:44.740 --> 02:34:50.460
[Guest]: making your destiny for you, in that if you do a good job and you produce something that's

02:34:50.460 --> 02:34:53.820
[Guest]: better, you see the results that flow as a result of that.

02:34:53.820 --> 02:34:59.620
[Guest]: That starts teaching the sense of efficacy and control that you have over your own destiny

02:34:59.620 --> 02:35:03.700
[Guest]: and outcomes, instead of saying it's fate, instead of saying it's someone else who's

02:35:03.700 --> 02:35:06.300
[Guest]: going to determine what happens to you.

02:35:06.300 --> 02:35:10.740
[Guest]: So all those reasons, you start learning these modern attitudes in a factory.

02:35:10.740 --> 02:35:15.980
[Guest]: I've always found that very convincing from the time that I first read it years ago.

02:35:15.980 --> 02:35:19.980
[Amit Varma]: And you know, another interesting sort of thought provoking bit was where you write

02:35:19.980 --> 02:35:24.140
[Amit Varma]: quote, a thought provoking edit by TN Ninan in the Business Standard many years ago on

02:35:24.140 --> 02:35:26.860
[Amit Varma]: the horrendous Nirbhaya rape has always haunted me.

02:35:26.860 --> 02:35:31.700
[Amit Varma]: He pointed out how different the victim and rapists were in the paths of modernity.

02:35:31.700 --> 02:35:35.860
[Amit Varma]: The victim and a friend were educated with good job prospects and formal occupations.

02:35:35.860 --> 02:35:40.180
[Amit Varma]: The rapists were all in informal, unstable occupations with nothing that either taught

02:35:40.180 --> 02:35:44.040
[Amit Varma]: them modern attitudes or gave them a stake in the existing system.

02:35:44.040 --> 02:35:48.140
[Amit Varma]: The difference was not where the victims and rapists had come from, but in the education

02:35:48.140 --> 02:35:52.340
[Amit Varma]: exposure and employment of their families, stop quote.

02:35:52.340 --> 02:35:55.940
[Amit Varma]: And you know, something that I've been saying for many years, and I discovered through your

02:35:55.940 --> 02:35:59.580
[Amit Varma]: book much to my dismay that Manmohan Singh has a quote that says exactly the same thing

02:35:59.580 --> 02:36:02.740
[Amit Varma]: is that India lives in many centuries at once.

02:36:02.740 --> 02:36:09.500
[Amit Varma]: And this is sort of a sort of a heartbreaking sort of instance of that, where an instance

02:36:09.500 --> 02:36:15.660
[Amit Varma]: of you know, the seen and the unseen, you know, it's it's kind of heartbreaking.

02:36:15.660 --> 02:36:19.540
[Amit Varma]: You've spoken about why manufacturing jobs matter more than services jobs, a bunch of

02:36:19.540 --> 02:36:20.540
[Amit Varma]: different reasons.

02:36:20.540 --> 02:36:27.620
[Amit Varma]: But you've also interestingly spoken about tourism, about how tourism can one be an industry

02:36:27.620 --> 02:36:28.900
[Amit Varma]: that booms in India.

02:36:28.900 --> 02:36:32.860
[Unknown]: And of course, we, you know, we have the raw material for it, which is the beauty and the

02:36:32.860 --> 02:36:34.800
[Amit Varma]: culture and all of that.

02:36:34.800 --> 02:36:37.900
[Amit Varma]: And two, why it can also be a significant modernizing influence.

02:36:37.900 --> 02:36:40.500
[Guest]: So tell me a bit about that and that opportunity.

02:36:40.500 --> 02:36:46.660
[Guest]: So you know, if you look around at where I mean, I have I talk about this particular

02:36:46.660 --> 02:36:51.420
[Guest]: resort Shillam between Bombay and Pune.

02:36:51.420 --> 02:36:56.140
[Guest]: And Shillam is in this very rural area.

02:36:56.140 --> 02:37:01.780
[Guest]: They've employed people from not by the thousand, but by the hundred from all the villages.

02:37:01.780 --> 02:37:05.580
[Guest]: They're very systematically, consciously recruited locally.

02:37:05.580 --> 02:37:11.940
[Guest]: And they've taught all of these girls and boys who've come from the villages how to

02:37:11.940 --> 02:37:15.260
[Guest]: behave with guests at a resort, you know.

02:37:15.260 --> 02:37:19.260
[Guest]: So they, and they just, they've learned, they've learned all kinds of things.

02:37:19.260 --> 02:37:23.580
[Guest]: They've learned hygiene, they've learned politeness, they've learned communication, they've learned

02:37:23.580 --> 02:37:29.500
[Guest]: dress, they've learned how to organize themselves, how to follow a schedule, you know.

02:37:29.500 --> 02:37:34.180
[Guest]: And their lives, the lives of them, their families have been transformed in these villages.

02:37:34.180 --> 02:37:40.220
[Guest]: The villages are becoming, I mean, I've been to Shillam maybe five or six times over 10

02:37:40.220 --> 02:37:41.220
[Guest]: years.

02:37:41.220 --> 02:37:46.300
[Guest]: And each time you go, you see that the villages that you go, that you drive through on the

02:37:46.300 --> 02:37:47.860
[Guest]: way to Shillam are getting more prosperous.

02:37:47.860 --> 02:37:50.420
[Guest]: There are now some shops that are opening up.

02:37:50.420 --> 02:37:55.220
[Guest]: The shops mean that people not only are selling things, but someone's buying them, you know.

02:37:55.220 --> 02:37:57.100
[Guest]: People have money to buy things and so on.

02:37:57.100 --> 02:38:04.260
[Guest]: And it's, you see, you see that transformative influence of people who are starting to get

02:38:04.260 --> 02:38:05.260
[Guest]: more modern.

02:38:05.260 --> 02:38:08.200
[Guest]: And the great thing is that they have jobs locally.

02:38:08.200 --> 02:38:10.820
[Guest]: They have jobs where they live in the villages.

02:38:10.820 --> 02:38:15.580
[Guest]: It doesn't mean that they have to all move to Pune or Bombay to get these modern jobs.

02:38:15.580 --> 02:38:18.460
[Guest]: They're getting their jobs, these good jobs right there.

02:38:18.460 --> 02:38:22.140
[Guest]: So that's the power that we have of tourism.

02:38:22.140 --> 02:38:26.540
[Guest]: I mean, we need a thousand Shillams all around the country.

02:38:26.540 --> 02:38:27.580
[Amit Varma]: And we have many more than that.

02:38:27.580 --> 02:38:33.100
[Amit Varma]: Like I remember many, like when we think of the typical tourist destinations in India,

02:38:33.100 --> 02:38:38.860
[Amit Varma]: it'll be like Kashmir in an erstwhile age, you know, Kerala, Rajasthan, and so on and

02:38:38.860 --> 02:38:39.860
[Amit Varma]: so forth.

02:38:39.860 --> 02:38:44.460
[Amit Varma]: But in 2003, when the tsunami struck, I remember I went with a relief team.

02:38:44.460 --> 02:38:46.540
[Amit Varma]: And I was also live blogging while I was doing that.

02:38:46.540 --> 02:38:48.820
[Amit Varma]: And I traveled down the coast of Tamil Nadu.

02:38:48.820 --> 02:38:52.620
[Amit Varma]: And at one hand, obviously, it's like a nightmare.

02:38:52.620 --> 02:38:53.620
[Amit Varma]: It's just horrible.

02:38:53.620 --> 02:38:59.020
[Amit Varma]: But later, when I thought about it in retrospect, I also realized that around those scenes of

02:38:59.020 --> 02:39:01.580
[Amit Varma]: devastation, there was great natural beauty.

02:39:01.580 --> 02:39:02.580
[Amit Varma]: Like I'm not kidding.

02:39:02.580 --> 02:39:05.260
[Amit Varma]: I've vacationed in Sri Lanka and so on and so forth.

02:39:05.260 --> 02:39:08.380
[Amit Varma]: Tamil Nadu has equal natural beauty, if not more.

02:39:08.380 --> 02:39:10.780
[Amit Varma]: You know, it's just absolutely gorgeous.

02:39:10.780 --> 02:39:14.780
[Amit Varma]: And the fact that we don't even think about it in terms of tourism and all that is a shame.

02:39:14.780 --> 02:39:19.060
[Guest]: And the Karnataka coast, I mean, if you, you know, the drive, I mean, the drive from Bombay

02:39:19.060 --> 02:39:21.060
[Guest]: to Goa is nice.

02:39:21.060 --> 02:39:24.460
[Guest]: The drive from Goa to Mangalore is spectacular.

02:39:24.460 --> 02:39:25.860
[Guest]: Wow, must make it.

02:39:25.860 --> 02:39:27.740
[Guest]: It is just spectacular.

02:39:27.740 --> 02:39:32.660
[Guest]: And you know, and it's just, and this, I mean, you just go in any direction.

02:39:32.660 --> 02:39:35.860
[Guest]: And there's so much to do and see.

02:39:35.860 --> 02:39:42.300
[Guest]: And, you know, I mean, we're country number, whatever, 20-something in the world tourism

02:39:42.300 --> 02:39:43.300
[Guest]: rankings.

02:39:43.300 --> 02:39:47.660
[Guest]: You know, country number one is France with 85 million tourists a year.

02:39:47.660 --> 02:39:50.540
[Guest]: OK, all these numbers are pre-pandemic, yeah?

02:39:50.540 --> 02:39:56.940
[Guest]: Now, 85 million tourists is a lot for a country of, what, 60 million people, right?

02:39:56.940 --> 02:39:59.940
[Guest]: Less than 60 million people, population of less than 60 million.

02:39:59.940 --> 02:40:01.780
[Guest]: We have 1.4 billion people.

02:40:01.780 --> 02:40:04.780
[Guest]: We can get tourists from all over the world.

02:40:04.780 --> 02:40:06.620
[Guest]: But we also need to get rid of some of our hangups.

02:40:06.620 --> 02:40:09.820
[Guest]: You know, we have these hangups that we all want people who, tourists who will come and

02:40:09.820 --> 02:40:11.140
[Guest]: stay at the Taj.

02:40:11.140 --> 02:40:12.460
[Guest]: Yeah, great.

02:40:12.460 --> 02:40:13.860
[Guest]: But that's a small number.

02:40:13.860 --> 02:40:19.100
[Guest]: We need people who will come and stay in four-star hotels and three-star hotels by the million.

02:40:19.100 --> 02:40:20.980
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, we want budget tourists.

02:40:20.980 --> 02:40:21.980
[Guest]: We want African tourists.

02:40:21.980 --> 02:40:23.420
[Guest]: We want Asian tourists.

02:40:23.420 --> 02:40:24.940
[Guest]: Exactly, exactly, exactly.

02:40:24.940 --> 02:40:27.220
[Guest]: We don't only want Europeans and Americans.

02:40:27.220 --> 02:40:30.340
[Guest]: We want people from all over the world.

02:40:30.340 --> 02:40:37.940
[Guest]: And I mean, you look at, OK, China is in a different place today because of the pandemic

02:40:37.940 --> 02:40:44.260
[Guest]: and its handling of the pandemic, where there are no Chinese tourists, which makes it attractive

02:40:44.260 --> 02:40:48.380
[Guest]: for anyone else to travel anywhere else in the world, by the way.

02:40:48.380 --> 02:40:56.100
[Guest]: But Chinese tourists have been a huge growth engine for most of Asia, for Japan, for South

02:40:56.100 --> 02:41:02.820
[Guest]: Korea, for Thailand, for the Philippines, for all of, almost all of Asia, but not for

02:41:02.820 --> 02:41:04.260
[Guest]: India.

02:41:04.260 --> 02:41:05.620
[Amit Varma]: Missed opportunity.

02:41:05.620 --> 02:41:06.780
[Amit Varma]: Huge missed opportunity.

02:41:06.780 --> 02:41:08.740
[Amit Varma]: So we have about like 20 minutes left.

02:41:08.740 --> 02:41:11.940
[Amit Varma]: There's so much to talk about your book anyway, even if we spoke for another three hours,

02:41:11.940 --> 02:41:16.420
[Amit Varma]: I don't think we'd cover it because it's just so rich in ideas and things to talk about.

02:41:16.420 --> 02:41:21.340
[Amit Varma]: I'll come straight away to what you call your three pillars of, you know, where India needs

02:41:21.340 --> 02:41:22.340
[Amit Varma]: to go.

02:41:22.340 --> 02:41:27.060
[Amit Varma]: Quote, putting this together, the government and policy environment is one of the three

02:41:27.060 --> 02:41:33.540
[Amit Varma]: pillars of leadership and inclusive, international, innovative and independent industry is a second.

02:41:33.540 --> 02:41:36.340
[Amit Varma]: Independent and effective institutions make up the third.

02:41:36.340 --> 02:41:39.500
[Amit Varma]: So you know, we've spoken a bit about the government and policy environment.

02:41:39.500 --> 02:41:46.500
[Amit Varma]: I also, let's talk about industry, where you point out how these four factors, inclusive,

02:41:46.500 --> 02:41:50.800
[Amit Varma]: international, innovative, independent, all of these are kind of important.

02:41:50.800 --> 02:41:54.660
[Amit Varma]: So I want you to briefly tell me a little bit about this and how you're thinking on

02:41:54.660 --> 02:41:57.180
[Amit Varma]: this evolve being an industry leader yourself.

02:41:57.180 --> 02:42:05.100
[Amit Varma]: And also the broader question I have to ask is that you've set out this vision where industry

02:42:05.100 --> 02:42:09.740
[Amit Varma]: can move in all these fantastic, beautiful directions.

02:42:09.740 --> 02:42:14.800
[Amit Varma]: Now my sense is that people are driven by self-interest, by incentives, right?

02:42:14.800 --> 02:42:18.800
[Amit Varma]: People respond to incentives and they will behave accordingly, therefore.

02:42:18.800 --> 02:42:20.420
[Amit Varma]: And where are those incentives coming from?

02:42:20.420 --> 02:42:23.900
[Amit Varma]: They can come from policy frameworks around them, they can come from the culture around

02:42:23.900 --> 02:42:24.980
[Amit Varma]: them.

02:42:24.980 --> 02:42:30.780
[Amit Varma]: And if companies don't behave in say, ABC way already, you know, what would make them

02:42:30.780 --> 02:42:31.780
[Amit Varma]: behave your way?

02:42:31.780 --> 02:42:37.300
[Amit Varma]: Now, it's one thing that there might be enlightened leadership in some companies like yours, where

02:42:37.300 --> 02:42:40.220
[Amit Varma]: you decide that this is a path we are going to take, we are going to be more inclusive,

02:42:40.220 --> 02:42:44.220
[Amit Varma]: we are going to, you know, blah, blah, blah, we are going to, you know, instead of running

02:42:44.220 --> 02:42:48.240
[Amit Varma]: from competition, we're going to go towards it like you decided in 91 and all that.

02:42:48.240 --> 02:42:53.540
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise, this question kind of struck with me that every industrialist will do what

02:42:53.540 --> 02:42:57.820
[Amit Varma]: is in her self-interest at a given point in time, that's determined by the incentives

02:42:57.820 --> 02:42:59.940
[Amit Varma]: from the environment around you.

02:42:59.940 --> 02:43:05.180
[Amit Varma]: And I don't see those incentives around either in policy or in culture that will make them

02:43:05.180 --> 02:43:06.660
[Guest]: move in these directions.

02:43:06.660 --> 02:43:09.640
[Guest]: So let's take the four I's.

02:43:09.640 --> 02:43:15.140
[Guest]: So the inclusive thing that I talk about the, you know, if industry needing to be more inclusive,

02:43:15.140 --> 02:43:18.540
[Guest]: I think will come largely through voluntary effort.

02:43:18.540 --> 02:43:23.900
[Guest]: It's difficult to change the policy framework to make Indian industry, you know, consciously

02:43:23.900 --> 02:43:26.660
[Guest]: more inclusive.

02:43:26.660 --> 02:43:33.180
[Guest]: One exception, which I'll come to in a sec, but by and large, it'll come from the CS,

02:43:33.180 --> 02:43:38.120
[Guest]: what I'm advocating is that from the CSR budgets of firms, focus the CSR budgets of firms on

02:43:38.120 --> 02:43:42.820
[Guest]: education, as it is education is the largest single item.

02:43:42.820 --> 02:43:47.700
[Guest]: In education, focus it on Karthik Muralidharan's idea, which is also in the new education policy

02:43:47.700 --> 02:43:50.260
[Guest]: of second standard outcomes.

02:43:50.260 --> 02:43:55.300
[Guest]: And if we can do that one thing as one big thing for all the schools that we in industry

02:43:55.300 --> 02:44:02.180
[Guest]: work with in any case, then we can transform the lives of millions of children each year.

02:44:02.180 --> 02:44:07.140
[Guest]: We can improve school outcomes for millions of children each year and therefore include

02:44:07.140 --> 02:44:11.420
[Guest]: millions more people each year in our growth process.

02:44:11.420 --> 02:44:14.060
[Guest]: That's one part of inclusion.

02:44:14.060 --> 02:44:19.140
[Guest]: The second part of inclusion, by the way, where we can, you know, the economist Gary

02:44:19.140 --> 02:44:23.500
[Guest]: Becker did a lot of work on discrimination theory many years ago.

02:44:23.500 --> 02:44:30.580
[Guest]: And his argument was that actually the first firms that move away from discrimination win.

02:44:30.580 --> 02:44:38.540
[Guest]: And if they can win very visibly and clearly economically, then in an incredibly short

02:44:38.540 --> 02:44:41.740
[Guest]: period of time, discrimination falls away.

02:44:41.740 --> 02:44:48.620
[Guest]: So the more we can get firms in India to see 1.4 billion people as the population from

02:44:48.620 --> 02:44:53.260
[Guest]: which to recruit, the more we will move in that direction.

02:44:53.260 --> 02:45:01.180
[Guest]: So we have to make inclusion and non-discriminatory employment, employing more women, employing

02:45:01.180 --> 02:45:04.980
[Guest]: more minorities, employing people from other geographies.

02:45:04.980 --> 02:45:10.180
[Guest]: We have to make that a really powerful business case.

02:45:10.180 --> 02:45:14.340
[Guest]: And when we make that a really powerful business case, I think it will flip quite fast.

02:45:14.340 --> 02:45:17.220
[Guest]: So now, how do we get that to happen?

02:45:17.220 --> 02:45:18.380
[Guest]: What do we need to do?

02:45:18.380 --> 02:45:25.500
[Guest]: I think it's examples, visibility, it'll take some time, but I think we have to move in

02:45:25.500 --> 02:45:26.500
[Guest]: that direction.

02:45:26.500 --> 02:45:27.500
[Guest]: Saatchi and Saatchi.

02:45:27.500 --> 02:45:28.500
[Guest]: Saatchi and Saatchi.

02:45:28.500 --> 02:45:29.500
[Guest]: I agree.

02:45:29.500 --> 02:45:32.460
[Guest]: I mean, I really think there's a lot to be said for getting some of these messages across

02:45:32.460 --> 02:45:34.500
[Guest]: in a very coherent, powerful way.

02:45:34.500 --> 02:45:40.420
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there's a study I like citing which shows that the most important factor in decision

02:45:40.420 --> 02:45:45.060
[Amit Varma]: making in any group, within a firm, in government or whatever, the most important factor is

02:45:45.060 --> 02:45:49.700
[Amit Varma]: not education or intelligence or whatever, it is diversity, that you have a diverse group

02:45:49.700 --> 02:45:54.300
[Amit Varma]: of people, you have the best decisions being made, added to what you pointed out, Becker's

02:45:54.300 --> 02:45:59.340
[Amit Varma]: study that, you know, you stop discriminating, you immediately, you have a competitive advantage.

02:45:59.340 --> 02:46:03.340
[Guest]: You know, in one of the run-up to one of the British elections, I was in the UK at that

02:46:03.340 --> 02:46:07.900
[Guest]: time, and I remember seeing a billboard that said, it was a very unfair billboard.

02:46:07.900 --> 02:46:13.260
[Guest]: It was from the Conservative Party, Margaret Thatcher's party, saying, it said, Labour

02:46:13.260 --> 02:46:14.860
[Guest]: says he's black.

02:46:14.860 --> 02:46:17.220
[Guest]: We say he's British.

02:46:17.220 --> 02:46:21.540
[Guest]: Completely unfair, but incredibly powerful communication, if you think of it.

02:46:21.540 --> 02:46:22.540
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:46:22.540 --> 02:46:26.980
[Guest]: I mean, if you just think of the, you know, and it was a powerful argument against discrimination

02:46:26.980 --> 02:46:33.580
[Guest]: in an interesting, somewhat, what would you call it, very deceitful way, but it was a

02:46:33.580 --> 02:46:34.580
[Guest]: very powerful way.

02:46:34.580 --> 02:46:37.100
[Guest]: I come to the other two, next two I's.

02:46:37.100 --> 02:46:40.980
[Guest]: Next two I's are international and innovative.

02:46:40.980 --> 02:46:46.460
[Guest]: For international, I think it's a, there's a clear policy role, which is open the economy

02:46:46.460 --> 02:46:51.680
[Guest]: up before industry says it's ready to be opened up.

02:46:51.680 --> 02:46:57.740
[Guest]: So allow imports as the best way of fostering exports.

02:46:57.740 --> 02:47:03.940
[Guest]: Because as an economist would say, a tax on imports is a tax on exports.

02:47:03.940 --> 02:47:08.440
[Guest]: So if you really want to see exports boom, bring down import tariffs.

02:47:08.440 --> 02:47:10.140
[Guest]: And we have an opportunity just now.

02:47:10.140 --> 02:47:12.020
[Guest]: The rupee is under some pressure.

02:47:12.020 --> 02:47:14.580
[Guest]: The RBI should not try to protect the rupee.

02:47:14.580 --> 02:47:17.620
[Guest]: It can protect a disorderly devaluation.

02:47:17.620 --> 02:47:21.060
[Guest]: But beyond that, it should let the rupee devalue.

02:47:21.060 --> 02:47:26.300
[Guest]: And use that devaluation as a way of then reducing tariffs on imported goods.

02:47:26.300 --> 02:47:29.300
[Guest]: That's for the finance ministry to do, or commerce ministry to do.

02:47:29.300 --> 02:47:36.500
[Guest]: So because that's a way of forcing Indian industry to be much more international.

02:47:36.500 --> 02:47:42.260
[Guest]: And from the industry side, we can help in that from CI, we can make it easier for firms

02:47:42.260 --> 02:47:47.240
[Guest]: to go overseas, to invest in different countries, enter new markets, and so on.

02:47:47.240 --> 02:47:51.980
[Guest]: On the innovation side, I've really wrestled with this question of why Indian industry

02:47:51.980 --> 02:47:55.980
[Guest]: invests as little as it does in in-house R&D.

02:47:55.980 --> 02:47:58.900
[Guest]: I don't think that's a policy point.

02:47:58.900 --> 02:48:01.900
[Guest]: I think that's very much of an industry point.

02:48:01.900 --> 02:48:04.540
[Guest]: I think it's for industry to fix on its own.

02:48:04.540 --> 02:48:11.140
[Guest]: We need to do some very visible benchmarking, where for different industries, and that's

02:48:11.140 --> 02:48:15.900
[Guest]: what we're trying to do now actually in CI, where for different industries, how much is

02:48:15.900 --> 02:48:20.540
[Guest]: invested in R&D versus the top firms in the industry worldwide?

02:48:20.540 --> 02:48:22.880
[Guest]: How many people are employed in R&D?

02:48:22.880 --> 02:48:25.180
[Guest]: What kind of qualifications do they have?

02:48:25.180 --> 02:48:28.980
[Guest]: What are the outcomes that they have in terms of new products and services that are introduced

02:48:28.980 --> 02:48:29.980
[Guest]: and so on?

02:48:29.980 --> 02:48:35.220
[Guest]: And I think through some of that benchmarking, if we start realizing that we actually do

02:48:35.220 --> 02:48:40.540
[Guest]: invest very little in R&D, and that awareness grows, then hopefully we'll start to see that

02:48:40.540 --> 02:48:41.540
[Guest]: change.

02:48:41.540 --> 02:48:46.700
[Guest]: I think that's a problem for industry to largely fix on its own, and industry associations

02:48:46.700 --> 02:48:50.580
[Guest]: like CI can play a key role.

02:48:50.580 --> 02:48:55.900
[Guest]: There's a second element to the innovation piece, which is a policy role, which is where

02:48:55.900 --> 02:48:58.700
[Guest]: public research and public R&D is done.

02:48:58.700 --> 02:49:03.020
[Guest]: It should be done within the higher education system instead of in autonomous R&D labs.

02:49:03.020 --> 02:49:07.340
[Guest]: That will improve the quality of the people coming out of the higher education system,

02:49:07.340 --> 02:49:10.660
[Guest]: which will help in-house R&D hugely.

02:49:10.660 --> 02:49:12.420
[Guest]: Last point on independence.

02:49:12.420 --> 02:49:21.860
[Guest]: I believe very much that our lack of speaking out, and the quote that you read earlier on,

02:49:21.860 --> 02:49:27.820
[Guest]: that the lack of speaking out is a reflection of decades of license rudge.

02:49:27.820 --> 02:49:33.940
[Guest]: And that mindset where we would keep going to the government for things, for licenses,

02:49:33.940 --> 02:49:40.260
[Guest]: for favors here, for incentives there, that mindset lives on.

02:49:40.260 --> 02:49:45.340
[Guest]: Even though the policy framework has largely changed since 1991.

02:49:45.340 --> 02:49:52.500
[Guest]: And we have to shed that mindset of going to the government and constantly asking for.

02:49:52.500 --> 02:49:58.060
[Guest]: I think that, unfortunately, will take the longest time to change.

02:49:58.060 --> 02:50:03.100
[Guest]: And I don't think we should wait for the government to be welcoming of criticism and input.

02:50:03.100 --> 02:50:06.640
[Guest]: It's for industry to make the change.

02:50:06.640 --> 02:50:15.260
[Guest]: If a hundred industrialists are independent and critical in speaking out, we're there.

02:50:15.260 --> 02:50:16.260
[Amit Varma]: But are they?

02:50:16.260 --> 02:50:17.260
[Amit Varma]: Are you an outlier?

02:50:17.260 --> 02:50:18.260
[Amit Varma]: No, no.

02:50:18.260 --> 02:50:19.260
[Guest]: I think we're too few.

02:50:19.260 --> 02:50:20.260
[Guest]: Too few?

02:50:20.260 --> 02:50:21.260
[Guest]: Far too few.

02:50:21.260 --> 02:50:22.260
[Guest]: Far too few.

02:50:22.260 --> 02:50:23.260
[Guest]: I mean, you know, you have people.

02:50:23.260 --> 02:50:30.620
[Guest]: Why is it that people like Rahul Bajaj have been, I think, justifiably revered by all

02:50:30.620 --> 02:50:31.620
[Guest]: of us?

02:50:31.620 --> 02:50:38.780
[Guest]: It's because there's so much of an exception, or Kiran Mazumdar.

02:50:38.780 --> 02:50:43.860
[Amit Varma]: There was a time where, you know, people like Ashok Desai and Montek Singh Ahluwalia and

02:50:43.860 --> 02:50:47.440
[Amit Varma]: all these people were also exceptions, you know, before the tide turned and today we

02:50:47.440 --> 02:50:48.540
[Amit Varma]: think of them as heroes.

02:50:48.540 --> 02:50:51.140
[Amit Varma]: So you know, there's something to be hopeful about.

02:50:51.140 --> 02:50:52.940
[Amit Varma]: My penultimate question.

02:50:52.940 --> 02:50:57.420
[Amit Varma]: At one point you write, quote, seeing our government up close left me both impressed

02:50:57.420 --> 02:50:58.420
[Amit Varma]: and depressed.

02:50:58.420 --> 02:51:02.820
[Amit Varma]: I was impressed by the intelligence, commitment and hard work of many of our past and present

02:51:02.820 --> 02:51:04.820
[Amit Varma]: ministers and senior bureaucrats.

02:51:04.820 --> 02:51:10.200
[Amit Varma]: I was depressed by how unprepared, unmindful of international best practice, diverted by

02:51:10.200 --> 02:51:15.140
[Amit Varma]: optics over content and petty some of these great minds were, stop quote.

02:51:15.140 --> 02:51:21.540
[Amit Varma]: And my question is there that how receptive are people to these ideas at three different

02:51:21.540 --> 02:51:22.580
[Amit Varma]: levels?

02:51:22.580 --> 02:51:26.580
[Amit Varma]: One is the level of government when you speak to policymakers and people who can actually

02:51:26.580 --> 02:51:27.940
[Amit Varma]: make decisions.

02:51:27.940 --> 02:51:32.500
[Amit Varma]: Two, at the level of your peers within the industry, which I think you've already answered,

02:51:32.500 --> 02:51:33.800
[Amit Varma]: you've said too few.

02:51:33.800 --> 02:51:38.740
[Amit Varma]: And three, at the level of the larger public, because, you know, these ideas need to be

02:51:38.740 --> 02:51:42.340
[Amit Varma]: part of the discourse and sadly they are not.

02:51:42.340 --> 02:51:45.800
[Amit Varma]: So you know, across these three, you know, what are your thoughts?

02:51:45.800 --> 02:51:52.340
[Guest]: So in the government, there are people who are receptive.

02:51:52.340 --> 02:51:59.060
[Guest]: And I give the story of a minister who after I'd written an article criticizing us dropping

02:51:59.060 --> 02:52:05.380
[Guest]: out of the RCEP negotiations, and I met him in a completely unrelated context two days

02:52:05.380 --> 02:52:06.500
[Guest]: later or something.

02:52:06.500 --> 02:52:09.860
[Guest]: And he said, he started by saying, I really liked your article.

02:52:09.860 --> 02:52:13.540
[Guest]: And he says, I would have phoned you to tell you, but I'm a loyal member of the government.

02:52:13.540 --> 02:52:15.380
[Guest]: So I did.

02:52:15.380 --> 02:52:17.940
[Guest]: But I mean, you know, so and I think there is this voice.

02:52:17.940 --> 02:52:25.460
[Guest]: There are these reformers within government who today, you know, among some ministers,

02:52:25.460 --> 02:52:29.380
[Guest]: some bureaucrats who want to do the right things.

02:52:29.380 --> 02:52:34.420
[Guest]: And I think their hand is strengthened if we speak out, whether in industry or whether

02:52:34.420 --> 02:52:37.220
[Guest]: in civil society, but certainly in industry.

02:52:37.220 --> 02:52:43.620
[Guest]: And so I think we strengthen reformers' hands when we're more independent.

02:52:43.620 --> 02:52:45.180
[Guest]: Shifting the Overton window, as it were.

02:52:45.180 --> 02:52:46.180
[Guest]: I think so.

02:52:46.180 --> 02:52:51.300
[Guest]: And I think it helps a great deal to do that.

02:52:51.300 --> 02:52:56.900
[Guest]: And by the way, I know several people in senior bureaucrats who have been very receptive.

02:52:56.900 --> 02:53:01.700
[Guest]: Some have read my book and have sent me nice messages.

02:53:01.700 --> 02:53:05.500
[Guest]: Some ministers and bureaucrats who have sent the book to have not heard from at all.

02:53:05.500 --> 02:53:11.140
[Guest]: So I don't know whether they've read it and didn't like it at all or whether they haven't

02:53:11.140 --> 02:53:12.140
[Guest]: read it yet.

02:53:12.140 --> 02:53:16.300
[Guest]: But my guess is it's the second, but I don't know.

02:53:16.300 --> 02:53:18.980
[Guest]: I'll find out at some point.

02:53:18.980 --> 02:53:24.460
[Guest]: On your third category, on sort of the public at large, you're right.

02:53:24.460 --> 02:53:30.140
[Guest]: I mean, you know, what I would love is that these kinds of questions on the role of the

02:53:30.140 --> 02:53:40.060
[Guest]: state, on the role of trade and an open trade policy, on the role of labor, labor laws and

02:53:40.060 --> 02:53:47.900
[Guest]: reform in building a more inclusive society and encouraging more women to work.

02:53:47.900 --> 02:53:55.180
[Guest]: On why we invest what we do in R&D and how we could do much more and better with it.

02:53:55.180 --> 02:54:02.980
[Guest]: On institutional independence and, you know, on the role of dissent and criticism.

02:54:02.980 --> 02:54:09.940
[Guest]: I really wish these kinds of questions were really seriously discussed and debated to

02:54:09.940 --> 02:54:16.060
[Guest]: a much greater extent, which is why I really appreciate this conversation, because it's

02:54:16.060 --> 02:54:17.180
[Guest]: so important for us.

02:54:17.180 --> 02:54:21.460
[Guest]: And I, you know, I want people to read my book, not to agree with it.

02:54:21.460 --> 02:54:25.460
[Guest]: I don't mind if they don't agree, but I don't mind if they disagree with everything that

02:54:25.460 --> 02:54:26.620
[Guest]: I say.

02:54:26.620 --> 02:54:30.220
[Guest]: But if they engage with these issues, I would be delighted.

02:54:30.220 --> 02:54:33.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, we need to talk more.

02:54:33.720 --> 02:54:39.060
[Amit Varma]: So my final question is, you know, and this is a common end for my episodes where I ask

02:54:39.060 --> 02:54:43.660
[Amit Varma]: my guests to recommend books or films or music that they absolutely love that, you know,

02:54:43.660 --> 02:54:45.540
[Amit Varma]: they take with them to a desert island.

02:54:45.540 --> 02:54:49.100
[Amit Varma]: You mentioned in your book that one of your top five favorite books is Exit, Voice and

02:54:49.100 --> 02:54:51.300
[Amit Varma]: Loyalty by Hirschman, which I love as well.

02:54:51.300 --> 02:54:54.620
[Amit Varma]: You mentioned during this conversation that Leave it to Smith is one of your top five

02:54:54.620 --> 02:54:55.620
[Amit Varma]: books as well.

02:54:55.620 --> 02:54:59.980
[Amit Varma]: Now, I don't know how many books that are in your top five, could be 15, could be 20.

02:54:59.980 --> 02:55:03.020
[Guest]: There are only five in my top five, but there are many close.

02:55:03.020 --> 02:55:07.700
[Amit Varma]: So give me the other three and then tell us about the close ones.

02:55:07.700 --> 02:55:11.780
[Guest]: And if you also want to talk about music and films, why not let's discover new things.

02:55:11.780 --> 02:55:12.780
[Guest]: Sure.

02:55:12.780 --> 02:55:17.580
[Guest]: So, India After Gandhi by Ram Chandra Guha is, I think, one of the great books of all

02:55:17.580 --> 02:55:21.780
[Guest]: time, one of the great histories, and it's wonderfully written.

02:55:21.780 --> 02:55:27.300
[Guest]: Many of Ram's books, you know, I mean, I think all of his books are worth reading and really

02:55:27.300 --> 02:55:28.300
[Guest]: great.

02:55:28.300 --> 02:55:34.900
[Guest]: But India After Gandhi is, to me, one of the great books for me of all time.

02:55:34.900 --> 02:55:39.020
[Guest]: The Wealth and Poverty of Nations by David Landis, I think, is a great economic history

02:55:39.020 --> 02:55:44.300
[Guest]: of the world and how the world got to be where it is, highly opinionated, quite amusing in

02:55:44.300 --> 02:55:47.780
[Guest]: different times, a good read.

02:55:47.780 --> 02:55:51.180
[Guest]: So it's a good book to read.

02:55:51.180 --> 02:55:56.980
[Guest]: It's a nice story, very opinionated, not balanced, but a good read.

02:55:56.980 --> 02:56:05.180
[Guest]: And then a little book by Alan Bennett called The Uncommon Reader, which is very funny.

02:56:05.180 --> 02:56:06.340
[Guest]: It's 100 pages.

02:56:06.340 --> 02:56:08.220
[Guest]: It's very funny.

02:56:08.220 --> 02:56:12.180
[Guest]: It's a great book for anyone who loves to read.

02:56:12.180 --> 02:56:22.060
[Guest]: And it's about the Queen of England becoming a great reader.

02:56:22.060 --> 02:56:24.660
[Guest]: That's why The Uncommon Reader.

02:56:24.660 --> 02:56:29.260
[Guest]: And, you know, how she gets hooked on to reading and what happens.

02:56:29.260 --> 02:56:33.880
[Guest]: And she starts reading first, you know, and she has the sense of duty.

02:56:33.880 --> 02:56:36.700
[Guest]: So if she opens a book, she has to finish it.

02:56:36.700 --> 02:56:40.120
[Guest]: Even books she doesn't enjoy, and then she starts reading more and more and she becomes

02:56:40.120 --> 02:56:41.120
[Unknown]: a great reader.

02:56:41.120 --> 02:56:43.300
[Guest]: So, I mean, it's a very amusing book.

02:56:43.300 --> 02:56:44.300
[Guest]: Those are the five.

02:56:44.300 --> 02:56:47.820
[Guest]: So very different, two fiction, three nonfiction.

02:56:47.820 --> 02:56:52.140
[Guest]: The ones that came very, there are also others that came very close, John Stuart Mill's On

02:56:52.140 --> 02:56:53.140
[Guest]: Liberty.

02:56:53.140 --> 02:56:55.260
[Guest]: It's a, I think, difficult book to read.

02:56:55.260 --> 02:57:02.660
[Guest]: It's, you know, it's 1850s prose at the end of the day, but the content is terrific.

02:57:02.660 --> 02:57:08.220
[Guest]: And it's a statement of liberalism like no other and the essence of what it is to really

02:57:08.220 --> 02:57:17.740
[Guest]: be free and why policy needs to keep in mind always how policies might infringe on one's

02:57:17.740 --> 02:57:19.380
[Guest]: individual liberty.

02:57:19.380 --> 02:57:23.740
[Guest]: There are many, many other books that I could come to.

02:57:23.740 --> 02:57:27.180
[Guest]: But anyway, those are the ones that there are.

02:57:27.180 --> 02:57:28.180
[Guest]: There are many others.

02:57:28.180 --> 02:57:34.980
[Guest]: There are others that Ram has written and, you know, his collections of essays like Patriots

02:57:34.980 --> 02:57:41.060
[Guest]: and Partisans and Democrats and Dissenters are also wonderful, I think, collections.

02:57:41.060 --> 02:57:42.660
[Guest]: And the whole of P.G.

02:57:42.660 --> 02:57:52.660
[Guest]: Stuart House, all 97 titles, but especially the Blanding series, the Jeeves series, the

02:57:52.660 --> 02:57:55.540
[Guest]: Smith series, the Uncle Fred series.

02:57:55.540 --> 02:57:56.540
[Amit Varma]: I mean, these are.

02:57:56.540 --> 02:58:00.700
[Amit Varma]: My childhood has come flooding back of lying in my bed in the summer afternoon, reading

02:58:00.700 --> 02:58:02.660
[Guest]: these paperbacks one by one.

02:58:02.660 --> 02:58:03.660
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:58:03.660 --> 02:58:06.980
[Guest]: You know, what I've recently discovered is Everyman.

02:58:06.980 --> 02:58:14.780
[Guest]: So Everyman is this these nice hardback editions of many classic books, and they've republished

02:58:14.780 --> 02:58:15.780
[Guest]: all the P.G.

02:58:15.780 --> 02:58:22.100
[Guest]: Woodhouse books on really good quality paper in caslon type, really nicely produced.

02:58:22.100 --> 02:58:27.140
[Guest]: And I'm sort of enjoying reading these nice physically produced book, P.G.

02:58:27.140 --> 02:58:28.140
[Guest]: Woodhouse's again.

02:58:28.140 --> 02:58:32.740
[Amit Varma]: I have an Everyman edition of George Orwell's collected essays, which I really love.

02:58:32.740 --> 02:58:33.740
[Amit Varma]: It's like a treasure.

02:58:33.740 --> 02:58:35.700
[Guest]: I keep dipping into it because he's such a good writer.

02:58:35.700 --> 02:58:41.180
[Guest]: So you take George, you know, the other ones have been in the top 10, by the way.

02:58:41.180 --> 02:58:45.180
[Guest]: So 1984 would be in there.

02:58:45.180 --> 02:58:51.980
[Guest]: Homage to Catalonia probably would not be, even though I think it is a great book.

02:58:51.980 --> 02:58:55.340
[Guest]: And maybe another Albert Hirschman, The Passions and the Interests would be in there.

02:58:55.340 --> 02:58:56.860
[Amit Varma]: I haven't read that.

02:58:56.860 --> 02:58:58.980
[Guest]: So what about music, films, anything?

02:58:58.980 --> 02:59:03.980
[Guest]: So music, films, very easy.

02:59:03.980 --> 02:59:09.420
[Guest]: I mean, I mainly listen to Western classical.

02:59:09.420 --> 02:59:13.260
[Guest]: And I started, I used to listen to a very wide range of Western classical.

02:59:13.260 --> 02:59:17.140
[Guest]: And as I've got older, I've got narrower.

02:59:17.140 --> 02:59:28.980
[Guest]: And I largely now listen to sort of Mozart, Beethoven, Brahms, Schubert, Schumann, those

02:59:28.980 --> 02:59:37.580
[Guest]: five Chopin, maybe six composers, heavy emphasis on piano music, some orchestral music, some

02:59:37.580 --> 02:59:39.620
[Guest]: favorite works.

02:59:39.620 --> 02:59:48.980
[Guest]: So the Brahms second piano concerto, the Beethoven fourth and fifth piano concertos, the Beethoven,

02:59:48.980 --> 02:59:54.220
[Guest]: well, the fourth, sixth, ninth symphonies.

02:59:54.220 --> 03:00:02.340
[Guest]: I mean, there are the Schubert impromptus, there are many, the Mozart, almost all the

03:00:02.340 --> 03:00:03.900
[Guest]: piano concertos.

03:00:03.900 --> 03:00:09.340
[Guest]: I mean, there's a stack that one could go with the Beethoven triple concerto.

03:00:09.340 --> 03:00:12.300
[Guest]: These are all wonderful works to listen to.

03:00:12.300 --> 03:00:16.460
[Guest]: And you can, I keep hearing them again and again and again.

03:00:16.460 --> 03:00:23.320
[Guest]: On film, my favorite movie of all time is, I like light films.

03:00:23.320 --> 03:00:27.220
[Guest]: I like comedies more than anything else.

03:00:27.220 --> 03:00:32.180
[Guest]: My favorite film is a movie called The Philadelphia Story.

03:00:32.180 --> 03:00:37.940
[Guest]: And my favorite actor and actress have tended to be Cary Grant and Catherine Hepburn, and

03:00:37.940 --> 03:00:39.980
[Guest]: they're both in it together.

03:00:39.980 --> 03:00:48.500
[Guest]: And then there are many others apart from Philadelphia Story, there's Casablanca, which

03:00:48.500 --> 03:00:54.420
[Guest]: is not a comedy, but it's quite funny as well, with Humphrey Bogart and Lauren Bacall.

03:00:54.420 --> 03:00:59.940
[Guest]: And there's a bunch of others.

03:00:59.940 --> 03:01:06.420
[Guest]: Most Cary Grant movies, most of the Catherine Hepburn, Spencer Tracy films.

03:01:06.420 --> 03:01:07.420
[Guest]: So quite a few.

03:01:07.420 --> 03:01:08.420
[Guest]: Great.

03:01:08.420 --> 03:01:15.740
[Amit Varma]: Noshad, thank you so much for coming on this show, writing such a thought provoking book

03:01:15.740 --> 03:01:19.020
[Amit Varma]: and sort of filling the air around me with positivity.

03:01:19.020 --> 03:01:22.940
[Guest]: I think at least today, I'll be a little less of a pessimist just because I had this conversation

03:01:22.940 --> 03:01:23.940
[Guest]: with you.

03:01:23.940 --> 03:01:24.940
[Guest]: So thank you.

